(7723,"_site_transient_pixcare_support_listable_kb","a:1:{s:10:\"categories\";a:9:{i:27;a:12:{s:7:\"term_id\";i:27;s:4:\"name\";s:15:\"Getting Started\";s:4:\"slug\";s:15:\"getting-started\";s:10:\"term_group\";i:0;s:16:\"term_taxonomy_id\";i:27;s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:14:\"ht_kb_category\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"parent\";i:0;s:5:\"count\";i:22;s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:10:\"term_order\";s:1:\"0\";s:8:\"articles\";a:6:{i:0;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:141;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 13:11:28\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 10:11:28\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:2676:\"<p>The demo content covers two main aspects that you should consider: it presents the strengths of our theme, and it showcases the smart features we provide. We highly recommend referring to it as a great inspiring starting point in order to see how much you can achieve with your upcoming website.</p>\n<h2><strong>Before you start</strong></h2>\n<p>To get the right results, please validate once again these details:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>make sure you installed and activated the required plugins</li>\n<li>if your site is already filled with content, please donât import demo data because your current content will be mixed with the new one and things will get messy</li>\n<li>double check that you have no errors in <em>Theme Dashboard â Status</em> so that the process will run as smooth as possible</li>\n</ul>\n<h2><b>Loading Demo Content</b></h2>\n\n<p>Itâs time to start importing the demo data by following these steps:Â <em>Website dashboard â Pixelgrade â Starter Content</em>. Click the <em>Import</em> button and wait until the process is finished. Normally, you shouldnât wait more than one to three minutes, but it depends on your Internet connection and speed.</p>\n\n<h2>FAQs</h2>\n<h4>What happens if the import process stops at some point?</h4>\n<p>If the import process seems to stop, then you should know that it might be just a common WordPress issue related to the <a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/Common_WordPress_Errors#Maximum_execution_time_exceeded\">maximum execution time</a> exceeded. There is a <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-maximum-execution-time-exceeded/\">plugin</a> that you can use to fix this easily. If you still struggle with it, read our friendly <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/faq/cant-finish-demo-data-import/\">article</a> about what you need to do to finish the demo data import.</p>\n<h4>Is the demo content free to use?</h4>\n<p>Because all the demo media content is under copyright, youâre not allowed to use it in any personal or commercial way. Instead, what you can do is to analyze it and get inspired to make your website at least as striking as our demo shows.</p>\n<h4>Why do you insert demo content?</h4>\n<p>We never liked the websites with <i>Lorem ipsum</i> and dumb images. We prefer real and authentic content (photos, text, multimedia) that matches the style and attitude of the theme we provide. Also, the demo content is available to expose our aesthetic approach and general look-and-feel that you can achieve it too.</p>\n<h4>Still struggling?</h4>\n<div>Don&#8217;t hesitate to reach us out. We have dedicated <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/services/\">services</a> to help you out in no time.</div>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:23:\"Adding the Demo Content\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:19:\"adding-demo-content\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2018-01-11 16:57:26\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2018-01-11 14:57:26\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=141\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:73:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/getting-started/adding-demo-content/\";}i:1;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:143;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"8\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 13:11:45\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 10:11:45\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:5616:\"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Besides the colors, fonts and spacing options, we know that at a certain point you will like to dig deeper and make <strong>advanced changes</strong> which include HTML, JavaScript or PHP code. The best way to make them happenÂ </span>while preserving the custom code changed from being overwritten the next time your theme is updated, is through <span style=\"font-weight: 400; font-size: 16px;\">a child theme. You can easily modify and add functionality without changing any code. So this is very important mostly because you donât lose the possibility to update the theme without losing your changes.</span></p>\n<h3><b>Download and install the Child Theme</b></h3>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">WordPress considers a </span><b>Child Theme</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> as an entirely separate theme so the process of installing is similar to the installing a Parent Theme. We recommend you follow these steps in order to get a Child Theme up and running.</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Download our s</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">tarter </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Child Theme</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Download our s</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">tarter </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Child Theme</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> You can do that by following <a href=\"http://pxg.to/listable-child-master\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><i>this link</i></a></span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\n</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Navigate to </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Appearance </span></i><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">â</span></i><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Themes</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and click </span><strong>Add New</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> button.</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Select </span><strong>Upload Theme</strong><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></i></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Click </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Browse </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">and choose the file you just downloaded and click </span><strong>Install Now</strong><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></i></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When the theme is installed click </span><strong>Activate</strong><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span></i></li>\n</ol>\n<h3><b>Start Customizing </b></h3>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The great part of this process is that you donât have to worry about the next session of theme&#8217;s updates. If you add customizations in the Child Theme all the changes you made will be automatically saved. </span></p>\n<h4><b>Adding custom CSS styles</b></h4>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are two different ways to add custom CSS to your Child theme â use an FTP client or the WordPress Dashboard. If the first method requires connecting to your site via FTP and editing the style.css file, the second one is much easier because you just have to go to your WordPress Dashboard site under </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Appearance â Editor</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Â andÂ select </span><b>style.css</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> from the right side and start adding your CSS. Simple as that.</span></p>\n<h4><b>Editing the </b><b><i>functions.php</i></b><b> file</b></h4>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If most files in your Child Theme overwrite the parent themeâs files (like style.css does for instance), functions.php file is pretty different. Instead of overwriting the parent themeâs functions.php file, you can simply load it in addition to it. Basically, your child themeâs functions.php file is loaded right before the parent themeâs functions.php file. You have to use a functions.php file only if you want to replace or modify a function from the Parent theme. </span></p>\n<h4><b>Editing or adding a new template file</b></h4>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Beyond CSS and Functions changes, we let you do structural changes to your theme by changing the PHP template files. In most scenarios, we recommend you to create a copy of the template files you want to change from the parent theme and make your modifications to the copied files. This way you make sure youâre on safe ground. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For example, if you want to modify the </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">content-single.php</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> template, just copy and paste this file to your Child Theme folder and do the changes you want there.</span></p>\n<p><b>Additional Resources</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"http://mediatemple.net/blog/tips/best-practice-why-and-how-to-create-a-child-theme-in-wordpress/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Why and How to Create a Child Theme in WordPress </span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">â MediaTemple</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/Child_Themes#How_to_Create_a_Child_Theme\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Child Themes</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> â WordPress.org</span></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:19:\"Using a Child Theme\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:17:\"using-child-theme\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2018-03-29 16:55:45\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2018-03-29 13:55:45\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=143\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:71:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/getting-started/using-child-theme/\";}i:2;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:6869;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"5\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-10 16:35:53\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-10 13:35:53\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:3253:\"<p>We want to help you start with the right foot in order to fully enjoy our WordPress theme. This why, you need to make sure you have a solid foundation for whatâs next by installing WordPress, the theme youâve chosen from our portfolio, and the right plugins. In this article, we will walk you through a friendly process of setting up the theme in a way thatâs correct and trustworthy.</p>\n<h2>Step 1 â Installing the theme</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Get the theme filesÂ by going to yourÂ <em>Envato accountÂ </em><em>âÂ <a href=\"http://themeforest.net/downloads\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Downloads</a>Â â Theme Name â Download âÂ Installable WordPress file only</em></li>\n<li>Back to theÂ <em>WordPress Dashboard</em>Â and navigate to<em>Â Appearance â Themes. C</em>lick<em>Â </em><strong>Add New</strong>Â button at the top of the page and go for theÂ <strong>Upload</strong>Â option.</li>\n<li>For the file upload, pick theÂ <em>ZIP archive</em>Â downloaded earlier from ThemeForest and clickÂ <strong>Install Now</strong>.</li>\n<li>Once the file has been uploaded, click theÂ <strong>Activate</strong>Â link.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Step 2 â Installing required and recommended plugins</h2>\n<p>Follow the top banner instructions andÂ install/activate the required and recommendedÂ plugins.</p>\n<p>After installation, follow theÂ <a href=\"https://wpjobmanager.com/document/installation/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Automatic Pages Setup</a>Â process from WP Job Manager plugin, and add these three pages:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Add a Listing</li>\n<li>Listing Dashboard</li>\n<li>Listings</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Below you can find the essential list of the free plugins:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wpjobmanager.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WP Job Manager</a>Â by Automattic and Mike Jolley (<a href=\"https://wpjobmanager.com/documentation/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Official Documentation</a>)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/customify/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Customify</a>Â by PixelGrade</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/comments-ratings/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Comments Ratings</a>Â by PixelGrade</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/category-icon/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Category Icon</a>Â by PixelGrade</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/pixtypes/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">PixTypes</a>Â by Pixelgrade</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>FAQ</h2>\n<h4 dir=\"ltr\">Missing the Stylesheet Error during the process?</h4>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Most of the time this happens because you are trying to install the <b>wrong .ZIP archive</b> you&#8217;ve downloaded from ThemeForest.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">When you try to download the theme you have just purchased you are presented with <b>2 different options</b> (besides the license file):</p>\n<ul>\n<li dir=\"ltr\"></li>\n<li><p>The first one is <b>Main Files</b> and this contains all the files provided including documentation, theme files, etc;</p>\n</li>\n<li>The second one is <b>Installable WordPress file</b> and this is just an archive of the theme files; <b>this is the .ZIP archive you want to use to install the theme</b>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:20:\"Installing the Theme\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:22:\"installing-theme-setup\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-10-27 11:21:20\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-10-27 08:21:20\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=6869\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:76:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/getting-started/installing-theme-setup/\";}i:3;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:7454;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-18 17:51:11\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-18 14:51:11\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:4628:\"<p>Like any website, your website needs a front page and Listable has a dedicated set of options in order to achieve this. Further below there is a step-by-step guide.</p>\n<h2>Step 1 â Create a &#8220;Home&#8221; page</h2>\n<p>From your site, WP dashboard, add a new page and name it &#8220;Home&#8221; or similar. Then find theÂ Page Attributes<strong>Â </strong>section in the right sidebar area and set theÂ <em>Template</em>Â toÂ <strong>Front Page</strong>. This template allows you to display aÂ <strong>Search</strong>Â field inside theÂ <em>Hero Area.</em></p>\n<p>Configure the Hero Area</p>\n<p>After selecting the Front Page template,Â <a href=\"http://cl.ly/image/3C1O2U3R1u3e\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">new options</a>Â appear, so you can manage theÂ <em>background</em>Â or theÂ <em>highlighted categories</em>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hero Area (Background):Â </strong>use this block to displayÂ aÂ random backgroundÂ between a gallery ofÂ <strong>images</strong>Â and a list ofÂ <strong>videos</strong>Â (self-hosted). To ensure the high contrast for text over image, we reduced the opacity to 50%.</li>\n<li><strong>Highlighted Categories:</strong>Â this section will display a list of selected categories to the bottom of the Hero Area. Using theirÂ <a href=\"http://cl.ly/image/0f1V1X0R1D1z\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">slugs</a>, you can specify which one to highlight. Also if their names areÂ <em>too long</em>Â to fit into one row you can use aÂ <em>placeholder</em>Â to show an alternative, smaller version: eg.Â <em>category (Cat)</em></li>\n<li><strong>Search Fields:Â </strong>to extend the search form, you can add theÂ <a href=\"http://cl.ly/0C1c0Y1L1D41/Search%20Menu%20-%20Front%20Page.png\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Categories and Location</a>Â fields directly to the Hero Area (seeÂ <a href=\"http://cl.ly/2X0S120X0y0D/Image%202016-01-08%20at%2010.13.30%20am.png\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">screenshot</a>). We were going with the single-field option for the demo as it has a better conversion rate, but depending on your situation, the other two fields might be more relevant to the user search.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Step 2 â Set a Static Front Page</h2>\n<p>Before going further, let&#8217;s put the above-created page on front page. By default, WordPress displays the latest posts there â to change that and show your new static &#8220;Home&#8221; page, follow these easy steps:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Launch the siteÂ <em>Customizer</em>Â and click on the Static Front Page tab on the left.</li>\n<li>Select theÂ <strong>Static Page</strong>Â option, then choose your new page from the<strong>Â Front Page</strong>Â drop-down.</li>\n<li>Click on theÂ <strong>Save &amp; Publish</strong>Â button to save your static page settings.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Step 3 â Customize the &#8220;Home&#8221; Page Layout through Widgets</h2>\n<p>Beneath the Hero area, you can add new sections through a Widgetized area. Go to your site Home page and on the top Admin bar, you will see a blue button calledÂ <a href=\"http://cl.ly/image/2a2p301j0N1o\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Customize Front Page Sections</a>. This is a useful shortcut to the Â <em>Appearance â</em>Â <em>Customizer â Widgets â Front PageÂ </em>area, where you can manage the content and order of the following widgets:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Listing Categories</strong>Â â Display a list of listing categories based on different criteria (eg. most popular, random) or specify which ones you want to show.</li>\n<li><strong>Listing Cards</strong>Â â Display a list of listings based on various criteria (eg. latest or featured listings from a specific category).</li>\n<li><strong>Spotlights</strong>Â â Emphasize some features of your website or use it as a step-by-step explaining process (eg.Â <em>How it Works</em>Â section).</li>\n<li><strong>Recent Posts</strong>Â â A list of the latest posts from your Blog section.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>FAQs</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-video-slideshow-hero-front-page/\">Can I have a Video or a Slideshow Hero on Front Page?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-make-logo-white-home-page/\">How can I make the Logo White on my &#8220;Home&#8221; page?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-place-advertisements-site-using-listable/\">Can I place advertisements on my site using Listable?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/remove-grey-overlay-front-page/\">How to remove the grey overlay from the Front Page?</a></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:41:\"Creating the âHomeâ Page (Front Page)\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:27:\"listable-creating-home-page\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 18:37:54\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 15:37:54\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=7454\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:81:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/getting-started/listable-creating-home-page/\";}i:4;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:7462;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-18 18:01:14\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-18 15:01:14\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:1932:\"<p>The <a href=\"https://demos.pixelgrade.com/listable/?page_id=12\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">&#8220;Listings Archive</a> page shows a record of your listings along with a location map, as well as filters for searching.</p>\n<p>After you&#8217;ve followed theÂ <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/getting-started/installing-theme-setup/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Getting Started</a> guide, at Step 2 you were advised to automatically create a &#8220;Listings&#8221; page. This is just a regular page with a simple shortcode that renders the listings:</p>\n<pre>[jobs]</pre>\n<p>This shortcode can take many arguments and you can use it for other pages too. Read more about it on the <a href=\"https://wpjobmanager.com/document/shortcode-reference/#section-1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Official Documentation</a> page.</p>\n<h3>Display Listings From a Specific Category</h3>\n<p>If you want to create a separate page that shows only listings from a specific category, you can use the shortcode above with the categories parameter:</p>\n<pre>[jobs categories=\"shops\"]</pre>\n<h3>Remove the Map From Listings Archive Page</h3>\n<p>Show the listings archive results without the map by using the <em>show_map</em> parameter:</p>\n<pre>[jobs show_map=\"false\"]</pre>\n<p>That&#8217;s it. Creating your listing page is very straight forward.</p>\n<h3>FAQs:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/fix-listing-archives-functionality/\">How to fix Listing Archives functionality?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-move-location-field-left-side-listings-page/\">How can I move the Location field on the Left Side of the listings page?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/change-description-content-listings-categories-pages/\">How do I change the Description Content on the Listings Categories pages?</a></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:36:\"Creating the \"Listings\" Archive Page\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:30:\"creating-listings-archive-page\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 18:25:20\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 15:25:20\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=7462\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:84:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/getting-started/creating-listings-archive-page/\";}i:5;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:7474;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-18 22:02:32\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-18 19:02:32\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:4151:\"<p>WithÂ ListableÂ we&#8217;ve adapted the famousÂ WP Job ManagerÂ interface, added the necessary features and create an easy to use the system so you can create, manage and monetize a local or global directory site.</p>\n<p>After you&#8217;ve followed theÂ <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/getting-started/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Getting Started</a>Â guide, you can start adding listings. Find out how below.</p>\n<h2>Adding and Managing Listings</h2>\n<p>There areÂ <strong>t</strong>wo ways to add a listing: through the<strong>Â </strong>WordPress DashboardÂ or directly from the Frontend, through theÂ &#8220;Add a Listing&#8221; page. If you&#8217;re handling the listings by yourself, add them throughÂ <em>DashboardÂ </em><em>â ListingsÂ </em><em>â Add NewÂ </em>page.</p>\n<p>There is a lovelyÂ step-by-step guide, right inside theÂ <em>Add New</em>Â page interface â this will surely get your way to adding your first listing.</p>\n<p><em>*Note:</em>Â You can still refer to theÂ <a href=\"https://wpjobmanager.com/document/adding-jobs-via-admin/#section-1\">Adding Jobs via Admin</a>Â article from the officialÂ <em>WP Job Manager documentation</em>, even if some fields were changed to make things easier, the structure is the same.</p>\n<h2>Adjusting The Listing Layout</h2>\n<p>The elementsÂ on the listing page are carefully placed to ensure a good hierarchy throughout the page. Depending on your needs,Â you can change their order and placementÂ using the availableÂ Widgetized Areas<strong>.Â </strong>Manage them fromÂ <em>Appearance â</em>Â <em>Customize â WidgetsÂ </em>andÂ navigateÂ to theÂ <em>Single Listing</em>Â page.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Single Listing Â»Â <strong>Content</strong>Â &#8211; The wider area where the main listing content should go.</li>\n<li>Single Listing Â»Â <strong>Sidebar Top</strong>Â &#8211; Placed at the top of the right sidebar, this area puts each widget in a visually different boxed container.</li>\n<li>Single Listing Â»Â <strong>Sidebar Bottom</strong>Â &#8211; Placed below the Sidebar Top, this area brings togetherÂ <em>all</em>Â the widgets under the same container.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Currently, theÂ following widgetsÂ are available:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Listing Â»Â <strong>Actions</strong>Â &#8211; Buttons like &#8220;Write a Review&#8221;, &#8220;Share&#8221; orÂ &#8220;Add to Favorites&#8221;.</li>\n<li>Listing Â»Â <strong>ContentÂ </strong>&#8211; Displays the main listing content.</li>\n<li>ListingÂ Â»Â <strong>Reviews</strong>Â &#8211; Displays a list of recent reviews and the submission form.</li>\n<li>Listing Â»Â <strong>Location MapÂ </strong>&#8211; A Map View of the listing location along with a Directions link to Google Maps.</li>\n<li>Listing Â»Â <strong>CategoriesÂ </strong>&#8211; The listing categories along with related icons.</li>\n<li>Listing Â»Â <strong>Hours</strong>Â &#8211; The Hours field content.</li>\n<li>Listing Â»<strong>Â Gallery ImagesÂ </strong>&#8211; The attached images in a gallery grid format</li>\n<li>Listing Â»Â <strong>TagsÂ </strong>&#8211; Used to display tags or amenities (optional using theÂ <a href=\"https://wpjobmanager.com/add-ons/job-tags/\">Tags</a>Â plugin)</li>\n</ol>\n<p><em>*<strong>Note:</strong>Â </em>Those widgets workÂ onlyÂ in the above-mentioned widget areas.</p>\n<h3>FAQs</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/modify-listing-address-format/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">How to modify the listing address format?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/change-default-zoom-level-map-widget/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">How do I change the default Zoom Level of the Map Widget?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/remove-extra-details-listing-urls-upon-submission/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Remove the extra details from listing URLs upon submission</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-listing-address-format-different-language/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">How can I have the listing address format different in each language?</a></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:34:\"Managing the \"Single Listing\" Page\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:28:\"managing-single-listing-page\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 18:23:12\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 15:23:12\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=7474\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:82:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/getting-started/managing-single-listing-page/\";}}}i:28;a:13:{s:7:\"term_id\";i:28;s:4:\"name\";s:17:\"Pages and Content\";s:4:\"slug\";s:17:\"pages-and-content\";s:10:\"term_group\";i:0;s:16:\"term_taxonomy_id\";i:28;s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:14:\"ht_kb_category\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"parent\";i:0;s:5:\"count\";i:54;s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:10:\"term_order\";s:1:\"1\";s:8:\"articles\";a:6:{i:0;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:6892;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"5\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-10 16:37:12\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-10 13:37:12\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:2362:\"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Setting up an eCommerce store is an increasingly way of making money online. The good news is that Listable offers integration with <strong>WooCommerce</strong> â the most popular plugin that allows you to create a shop on your WordPress website. In this article, weâll show you how to set up an online store where you can list and sell both physical and digital products.</span></p>\n\n<h2><b>Install WooCommerce plugin and start the Setup Wizard</b></h2>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">One of the greatest things about <strong>WooCommerce</strong> is that itâs not just the most powerful tool to create a shop, but their authors constantly improved the way of use and they made it incredibly user-friendly. Right after the plugin is activated, a SetupÂ Wizard starts and you just have to fill in the required details The Setup Wizard takes care of everything for you â it creates the Shop pages, helps you add all the details about the Shop, about the products and the payments and it even gives you the opportunity to import demo products, so you can have a starting point for your shop.Â </span></p>\n<div align=\"center\"><iframe class=\"wistia_embed\" title=\"Wistia video player\" src=\"https://fast.wistia.net/embed/iframe/mqu1za100z\" name=\"wistia_embed\" width=\"400\" height=\"225\" frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\n<p>All these details can be edited whenever you want by going to your WordPress Dashboard at <em>WooCommerce â Settings</em> section. Also, it&#8217;s good to know that the entire Setup Wizard can be re-started if needed. To do that, when you are on WooCommerce Dashboard, click on Help Button from the top bar and click <strong>Setup Wizard</strong> button (<a href=\"https://cl.ly/0d1X082x1N2T\">video capture</a>).</p>\n<p>Depending on your needs, you can extend the functionalities of WooCommerce with the following plugins: <a href=\"https://woocommerce.com/products/woocommerce-subscriptions/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Subscriptions</a>, <a href=\"https://woocommerce.com/products/woocommerce-bookings/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Bookings</a>, and others. You can read more about that <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/plugins-integrations/premium-plugins-extend-listable-functionality/\">here.</a></p>\n\n\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:25:\"Adding an eCommerce Store\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:22:\"adding-ecommerce-store\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2018-05-03 15:25:46\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2018-05-03 12:25:46\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=6892\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:78:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/adding-ecommerce-store/\";}i:1;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:7611;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"4\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 15:47:26\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 12:47:26\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:3656:\"<p>When you click the main <strong>Search</strong> field in our <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/demos/listable/\">demo</a> you will be presented with a drop-down menu that gives you some suggestions about the things that are promoted on the website â this is a great way for you to encourage visitors to explore the site &#8211; it will appear both on the Front Page hero and in the Header of the rest of the site.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://i0.wp.com/cl.ly/image/3k341H2p1g1p/Screen%20Recording%202015-11-25%20at%2002.50%20pm.gif\" /></p>\n<p>To add those links, we&#8217;ve envisioned a simple yet powerful and flexible system (see <a href=\"https://cl.ly/381K3D1g050B/annotate\">screenshot</a>). We will use the standard WordPress <strong>Menus</strong> â let&#8217;s get started:</p>\n<h3>Step 1 â Add the Keywords field to the front-page</h3>\n<p>The search menu is added to the Keywords field from front-page. You just have to edit the front-page and make sure that the <strong>Keywords</strong> box is checked (see <a href=\"https://cl.ly/122m0P1m2r27\">screenshot</a>).</p>\n<h3>Step 2 â Create the Search Menu</h3>\n<p>The very first move is to go to <em>Appearance â Customize â Menus</em> and click on <strong>Add Menu</strong> button to <a href=\"http://easywpguide.com/wordpress-manual/appearance/updating-the-menu/adding-a-new-menu/\">create a new menu</a>, then give it a name like <em>Search Menu</em>, for instance.</p>\n<h3>Step 3 â Assign the Search Menu</h3>\n<p>At this point, you have to go to <em>Appearance â Customize â Menus â Managed Locations</em> section and select the <em>Search Menu</em> that you just created in the <em>Search Menu</em> field.</p>\n<h3>Step 4 â Add Items to the Menu</h3>\n<p>You have to go back to <em>Edit Menus</em> area. From the left section, you can add links to the desired sections: <em>listings categories, tags, regions </em>or<em> even regular pages.</em></p>\n<p>If the items that you want to add to your menu are not visible, click the <em>Screen Options</em> button in the top right corner of your screen and make sure that you checked all the needed elements (see <a href=\"http://cl.ly/image/3H0k343s1l0n\">screenshot</a>)</p>\n<h3>Step 5 â Add Description</h3>\n<p>In the same <em>Screen Options</em> section, there is a <em>Description</em> option that you should check if you want to have small explanatory notes for each menu item (see <a href=\"http://cl.ly/image/1O1g0m1i3608\">screenshot</a>)</p>\n<h3>Step 6 â Add Icon</h3>\n<p>For icons, you need to install the FREE <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/menu-icons/\">Menu Icons</a> plugin. After activation, a new block will appear on the left side from where you can select the icon sources. After that, each menu items has a new icon field that you can use (see <a href=\"http://cl.ly/image/0Y0K1M433t3A\">screenshot</a>)</p>\n<p><strong>Additional Readings:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Get the <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/menu-icons/\">Menu Icons</a>Â plugin</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://easywpguide.com/wordpress-manual/appearance/updating-the-menu/adding-a-new-menu/\">Adding a New Menu</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/header-and-footer/managing-your-navigation/\">Managing your Navigation</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/managing-secondary-menu/\">Managing the Secondary Menu</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/add-current-username-navigation-menu/\">How to add the Current Username to the Navigation Menu?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/create-log-link-menu/\">How to Create a Log Out Link in Your Menu</a></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:36:\"Managing the Search Suggestions list\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:32:\"managing-search-suggestions-list\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 16:58:34\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 13:58:34\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=7611\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:88:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/managing-search-suggestions-list/\";}i:2;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:7616;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"4\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 15:52:54\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 12:52:54\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:1471:\"<p>Allow visitors to share your content on social media by adding Share buttons to your listings.</p>\n<h3>Step 1 â Install the Jetpack plugin</h3>\n<p>The Sharing tools are powered by the famous <a href=\"https://jetpack.me/\">Jetpack</a> (Automattic) plugin. It should come as a <em>recommended plugin</em> after theme activation.</p>\n<h3>Step 2 â Activate the Sharing module</h3>\n<p>Now go to<em> Jetpack â Settings</em> in your site&#8217;s dashboard and make sure you have activated the <em>Sharing module.</em></p>\n<h3>Step 3 â Add Sharing Buttons</h3>\n<p>You can finally add the sharing buttons to your listings in four short steps:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Navigate to <em>Settings â Sharing</em> in your site&#8217;s dashboard.</li>\n<li>Under the<em> Sharing Buttons</em>, drag and drop the services you want to use into the Enabled Services area.</li>\n<li>Choose your preferred button style and where you would like the buttons to appear.</li>\n<li>Save! That&#8217;s it!</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Need more details? Then read <a href=\"https://jetpack.me/support/sharing/\">this article</a> from the official documentation.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Additional Readings:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/how-do-i-add-extra-social-media-profiles/\">How do I add Extra Social Media Profiles?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-edit-add-new-listing-fields/\">Can I edit or add new listing fields?</a></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:32:\"Adding Share Buttons to Listings\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:29:\"adding-share-buttons-listings\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 16:46:44\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 13:46:44\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=7616\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:85:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/adding-share-buttons-listings/\";}i:3;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:7620;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"4\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 16:02:49\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 13:02:49\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:3634:\"<p>By linking a product to a listing, you can increase business sales and offer all kind of special offers to your visitors (eg. <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/demos/listable/listings/london-imax/\">Movie Tickets</a>). In order to do that, let&#8217;s follow the steps below:</p>\n<blockquote><p>To link WooCommerce products to your listings you need the <a href=\"https://astoundify.com/downloads/wp-job-manager-products/\">WP Job Manager &#8211; Products</a> plugin (sold separately).</p></blockquote>\n<h3>Step 1 <b>â</b>Â Install the WooCommerce and Products Plugin</h3>\n<p>You must first purchase, install and activate the <a href=\"https://astoundify.com/downloads/wp-job-manager-products/\">WP Job Manager &#8211; Products</a> (Astoundify) plugin along with the free <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/woocommerce/\">WooCommerce</a> one.</p>\n<h3>Step 2 <b>â</b>Â Add theÂ Listing Â» ProductsÂ Widget</h3>\n<p>After installation, a new <em>Listing &#8211; Productswidget will be available to be placed in the Single Listing page.</em></p>\n<p>Navigate to a listing page and in the <em>Admin Bar</em>, click on the <em>Customize Listings LayoutÂ </em>(<a href=\"http://cl.ly/411X121L3z1M\">screenshot</a>) â select <em>Listing Â» Sidebar Top</em> widget area â <em>Add a Widget</em> â <em>Listing Â» Products</em>.</p>\n<p>Now all the linked products will appear on the right sidebar of the associated listing.</p>\n<h3>Step 3 <b>â</b>Â Add a Product</h3>\n<p>Start by adding a WooCommerce product by following the <a href=\"https://docs.woothemes.com/document/managing-products/\">Adding and Managing Products</a> guide. Few additional notes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>To better keep track of the products, I recommend to name them by including the listing title on it (eg. Movie Night Popcorn atÂ <em>IMAX Cinema.</em>).</li>\n<li>Use theÂ <em>Product Short Description</em>Â field if you want to add a small explanatory description.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Step 4 <b>â</b>Â Link the Product to a Listing</h3>\n<p>After <em>Products</em> plugin installation, a new <em>Select Your Services &amp; Products</em> field appear both on the backend and frontend of your Listing editing page. Use it to select your newly created product (<a href=\"http://cl.ly/071u1C0o1A00\">screenshot</a>).</p>\n<p><strong>That&#8217;s it!</strong> Now the product should be beautifully displayed in the listing page. See a <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/demos/listable/listings/london-imax/\">live example</a> from the demo.</p>\n<h4>Advanced Functionality</h4>\n<p>Now that the basic functionality is settled, you can go even further and add more functionality to your products.</p>\n<p>You can use the <a href=\"http://www.woothemes.com/products/woocommerce-bookings/\">WooCommerce Bookings</a> plugin to add various date based bookings/reservations (check those <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/demos/listable/listing-tag/reservations/\">listings</a>) or the <a href=\"http://www.woothemes.com/products/product-vendors/\">Product Vendors</a> plugin to let business owners add and manage their own products, and you earn commissions in a multi-vendor marketplace.</p>\n<h3>Additional Resources:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/adding-bookings-listings/\">Adding Bookings to Listings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/improving-checkout-process/\">Improving the Checkout Process</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.woothemes.com/woocommerce/\">WooCommerce</a> plugin</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://astoundify.com/downloads/wp-job-manager-products/\">WP Job Manager &#8211; Products</a> plugin</li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:33:\"Adding Products/Deals to Listings\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:29:\"adding-productsdeals-listings\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-06-22 10:46:37\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-06-22 07:46:37\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=7620\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:85:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/adding-productsdeals-listings/\";}i:4;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:7627;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"4\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 16:08:26\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 13:08:26\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:1844:\"<blockquote><p>To add Bookable Products to your listings you need the <a href=\"http://www.woothemes.com/products/woocommerce-bookings/\">WooCommerce Bookings</a> + <a href=\"https://astoundify.com/downloads/wp-job-manager-products/\">Products</a> plugins (sold separately).</p></blockquote>\n<p>Using the powerful WooCommerce Booking<strong>s</strong> plugin with Listable, you can add various date based bookings, like:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Reservation Calendar for <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/demos/listable/listings/portobello/\">Restaurants</a></li>\n<li>Room Reservation for <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/demos/listable/listings/russell-hotel/\">Hotels</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/demos/listable/listings/jumeirah-grosvenor-apartments/\">Apartments</a> Rental Services</li>\n<li>..and a lot <a href=\"https://support.woothemes.com/hc/en-us/sections/200444723-Bookings\">more</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>In order to add a Bookings to your listings, follow the same steps from <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/adding-productsdeals-listings/\">Adding Products/Deals to Listings</a> guide, only that on the third step select the <a href=\"https://docs.woothemes.com/document/creating-a-bookable-product/\">Bookable Product</a> type.</p>\n<p>For in-depth documentation check out the official <a href=\"https://docs.woothemes.com/documentation/plugins/woocommerce/woocommerce-extensions/bookings/\">WooCommerce Bookings Documentation</a>.</p>\n<h3>Additional Reading:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/adding-productsdeals-listings/\">Adding Products/Deals to Listings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.woothemes.com/document/getting-started-with-bookings/\">Getting Started with Bookings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.woothemes.com/document/creating-a-bookable-product/\">Creating a Bookable Product</a></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:27:\"Adding Bookings to Listings\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:24:\"adding-bookings-listings\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-05-30 22:12:42\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-05-30 19:12:42\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=7627\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:80:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/adding-bookings-listings/\";}i:5;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:7631;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"4\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 16:11:59\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 13:11:59\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:1283:\"<p>When you&#8217;re using WooCommerce for selling products, depending on your needs, you may see that the users struggle to fill all the unnecessary fields from the checkout page. See how the <a href=\"http://cl.ly/image/320h0O2V3S3D\">Standard Checkout</a> looks. Let&#8217;s see how can we make it better.</p>\n<p>By following just two easy steps, you will significantly improve the checkout user experience:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Make the <em>Buy Now</em> button to go directly to the Checkout and skip the intermediary Cart page. Install the <a href=\"https://ro.wordpress.org/plugins/woocommerce-direct-checkout/\">WooCommerce Direct Checkout</a> plugin.</li>\n<li>Remove the unnecessary fields or sections from the checkout page using <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/woocommerce-checkout-manager/\">WooCommerce Checkout Manager</a>.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>See how the <a href=\"http://cl.ly/image/0F2y18450b3b\">Improved Checkout</a> looks now.</p>\n<p>That&#8217;s it! You will thanks us later.</p>\n<p>Additional Resources:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/adding-productsdeals-listings/\">Adding Products/Deals to Listings</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/adding-bookings-listings/\">Adding Bookings to Listings</a></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:30:\"Improving the Checkout Process\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:26:\"improving-checkout-process\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-05-30 22:11:42\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-05-30 19:11:42\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=7631\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:82:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/improving-checkout-process/\";}}s:8:\"children\";a:1:{i:0;a:12:{s:7:\"term_id\";i:37;s:4:\"name\";s:4:\"Tips\";s:4:\"slug\";s:4:\"tips\";s:10:\"term_group\";i:0;s:16:\"term_taxonomy_id\";i:37;s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:14:\"ht_kb_category\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"parent\";i:28;s:5:\"count\";i:9;s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:10:\"term_order\";s:1:\"0\";s:8:\"articles\";a:4:{i:0;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:148;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 13:14:49\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 10:14:49\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:2917:\"<p>WordPress comes with an amount of great benefits. One of them is the simple fact is fully translated into over 65 languages, and it can be adjusted to your language&#8217;s characteristics as well. We know that this is important since your audience might be pretty narrow (e.g. Spanish natives).</p>\n<p>You should know that changing the website language from the dashboard area is not enough. Your website&#8217;s structure is formed of different parts of posts, pages, menus or widgets. The content of those sections can be added directly to your language. However, there are strings attached, both from the theme and plugins, that you need to translate. Let&#8217;s take the following scenario: you have a blog website, and at the end of each article you can have a Read more part. Those specific words should be translated into your native language in order to facilitate access.</p>\n<p>The .PO file includes the original texts and the translations in two columns. The .MO file incorporates the exact same contents as PO file. Keep in mind that the two files differ in their format. While a PO file is easy for humans to read, MO files are compiled and very easy for computers to read. Nonetheless, WordPress gets translations from .MO files.</p>\n<p>Here are the steps you have to take in order to translate your website:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Change the language by going to Settings Â» General Â» Site Language field;</li>\n<li>Go to <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/translate/projects/\">this link</a>;</li>\n<li>Select the theme that youÂ are using;</li>\n<li>Click on the language you would like to translate your website;</li>\n<li>You can suggest a new translation for any of the English original strings, seen on the left. Just click on Details button from the end of the line and add your suggestion;</li>\n<li>Once you finished your translation, go to the bottom of the page and select to Export all current as Portable Object Message Catalog (.po);</li>\n<li>You need to export one more file, the Machine Object Message (.mo),Â the same way you did on step 6;</li>\n<li>Go to <a href=\"https://make.wordpress.org/polyglots/teams/\">this link</a>;</li>\n<li>Find the WP Locale for the language you want to translate your website into.</li>\n<li>Rename both PO and MO files this way: themename-locale.po and themename-locale.mo. For example, if the theme is called Julia and you want to translate it in French, your files will be called julia-fr_FR.po and julia-fr_FR.mo;</li>\n<li>Upload the translation files, through FTP:</li>\n<li>\n<ol>\n<li>The theme translation files need to be added to wp-content/languages/themes folder;</li>\n<li>The plugins translation files need be added to wp-content/languages/plugins folder.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>FAQs</h2>\n<h3>Are your themes compatible with WPML?</h3>\n<p>Yes â here is the official list of <a href=\"https://wpml.org/developer/pixelgrade/\">WPML certified themes</a>.</p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:29:\"Translate Your WordPress Site\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:29:\"translate-your-wordpress-site\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-11-16 15:33:25\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-11-16 13:33:25\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=148\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:90:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/tips/translate-your-wordpress-site/\";}i:1;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:6914;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"5\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-10 16:36:00\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-10 13:36:00\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:7574:\"<p>Speed is the ultimate frontier of the web nowadays. Everybody wants it, especially since GoogleÂ <a href=\"http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.ro/2010/04/using-site-speed-in-web-search-ranking.html\">announced</a>Â that page speed is a big factor in search rankings. More recently evenÂ <a href=\"http://googlewebmastercentral.blogspot.ro/2013/06/changes-in-rankings-of-smartphone_11.html\">mobile site speed</a>Â is a big factor.</p>\n<p>So yes we need it. But there is only so much a theme (and us as theme developers) can do in terms of <a href=\"https://kinsta.com/blog/optimize-images-for-web/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">speed optimizations</a>. Sure we can be careful not to do silly things like a bunch load of MySQL queries, load the right image sizes, reduce the number of requests for static resources, etc. But these are only the tip of the iceberg in terms of site speed.</p>\n<p>The huge gains in terms of <a href=\"https://websitesetup.org/how-to-speed-up-wordpress/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">site speed</a> are achieved outside the theme. So let&#8217;s get rolling with some tips for you.</p>\n<h2>Caching is King</h2>\n<p>When it comes to WordPress, that is a CMS that generatesÂ <strong>dynamic</strong>Â pages, the first and the most important thing we can do is remove the dynamic from the equation. It is a well known fact that static pages are served by the webserver much much faster (because it removes processor and MySQL speed from the equation).</p>\n<p>In WordPress, this can be achieved withÂ <strong>caching pluginsÂ </strong>that will generate temporary static HTML files for your pages/posts, while managing their refresh on content update.</p>\n<p>The most used caching plugins areÂ <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/w3-total-cache/\">W3 Total Cache</a>Â andÂ <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-super-cache/\">WP Super Cache</a>. We tend to lean towards W3 Total Cache because it offers more speed, although being somewhat more complicated. But both are really good and will work just fine. They still need some configuration work but nothing that an average WordPress user can&#8217;t manage.</p>\n<p>The most important section in these plugins is theÂ <strong>Page Cache</strong>, this one being the one that generates those static HTML files. We recommend you not to use their JS and CSS minification since it most likely will break things if not properly configured. They also offer database and object caching; we leave this to you to decide, but it won&#8217;t make much of a difference.</p>\n<h2>Image Optimization</h2>\n<p>Nowadays sites tend to be full of images, much more so then a couple of years ago. The web has become much more visual. This raises the concern that those images might not be that well optimized, resulting in huge page sizes (1,2,3 and evem more MB).</p>\n<p>So we need to make sure that our image file size is at it&#8217;s lowest without loosing quality of course. Thankfully there are a couple of WordPress plugins out there that focus on just this problem. They either use scripts installed on your server (like pngcrush, advpng, jpegcrush, etc &#8211; you will need to talk to your host about these) or online services that do the crunching for you.</p>\n<p><strong>We recommend</strong>Â these plugins:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/ewww-image-optimizer/\">EWWW Image Optimizer</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-smushit/\">WP Smush.it</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/prizm-image/\">Prizm Image</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Also you should be aware that when switching themes, you most likely need toÂ <strong>regenerate your thumbnails</strong>Â (that are autogenerated on image upload) so you will allow the new theme to use the best image sizes it was intended to. For this we recommend these plugins:Â <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/force-regenerate-thumbnails/\">Force Regenerate Thumbnails</a>Â andÂ <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/plugins/ajax-thumbnail-rebuild/\">AJAX Thumbnail Rebuild</a>.</p>\n<h2>A good host is worth a 1000 optimizations</h2>\n<p>There&#8217;s simply no way around this. You simply can&#8217;t expect to pay for a VW and get a Ferrari. If speed is a major concern to you then on top of your list must be getting a proper <a href=\"https://firstsiteguide.com/wordpress-hosting/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">hosting</a>.</p>\n<p>When <a href=\"https://www.designbombs.com/best-wordpress-hosting/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">talking of hosting services</a>, there are 2 cases: you can either go with a shared hosting or a dedicated one. We highly recommend you to read this in-depth analysis about theÂ <a href=\"https://www.wpkube.com/best-managed-wordpress-hosting/\">9 best options for managed WordPress Hosting Compared</a>.</p>\n<p><strong>Shared hosting</strong>Â is generally cheap because it allows the hoster to cram into the same physical server a large number of clients. When this happens you must be aware that your site is in a constant battle with many other sites for resources, mainly CPU and HDD speed. So you are pretty much in the hands of destiny in terms of speed. If you are lucky to not be sharing servers with some resource hungry websites, you might be good, but you never know. This doesn&#8217;t mean that there aren&#8217;t shared hosting offerings out there that offer premium speed (for the right price) taking the burden of managing your own server out of your hands. You just have to be careful and know that you get what you pay for.</p>\n<p>The second option when it comes to hosting your precious site is<strong>Â the dedicated server</strong>Â (either a VPS or a true dedicated server). If we are talking about cloud based servers (VPS) the costs are not that big but the benefits are huge when compared to shared hosting services. The dedicated servers are generally expensive and are aimed at pros, so we won&#8217;t discuss them here. If you are not that tech savvy you may need a managed VPS that will add additional costs, but it is well worth it.</p>\n<p>Let me give youÂ <strong>some advantages of having your own VPS</strong>, in no specific order:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>guaranteed CPU access</strong>;</li>\n<li><strong>high speed HDDs</strong>;</li>\n<li><strong>lower response times</strong>Â (that damn time to first byte);</li>\n<li>you can activateÂ <strong>server side gzip compression</strong>Â that will greatly reduce the size of your static resources (CSS, JS and image files);</li>\n<li>you can remove the cookies on static resources &#8211;Â <strong>cookie-less domain</strong>Â (you will see this popping up in Page Speed);</li>\n<li>you can quit using the Apache web server and go with a much speedierÂ <strong>Nginx web server</strong>;</li>\n<li>you can useÂ <strong>server-side caching</strong>Â (much faster than file based one);</li>\n<li>you canÂ <strong>configure MySQL</strong>Â to your own website necessities hence more speed;</li>\n<li>you can have load balancers, but we are getting to technical here &#x1f642;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>As you can see most of the things that are required to get that high Google Page Speed score are out of the theme&#8217;s hands. They need server-side configuration and tools.</p>\n<p>I hope this brief introduction into the intricacies of optimizing your site has enlighten you somewhat on the steps you need to take to increase you speed so your visitors and Google like you more.</p>\n<h4>Still struggle?</h4>\n<p>Write us down an e-mail at <strong>hello@pixelgrade.com</strong>, and we will gladlyÂ assist you duringÂ this process.</p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:31:\"Speeding Up Your WordPress Site\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:23:\"speeding-wordpress-site\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2018-05-21 15:12:18\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2018-05-21 12:12:18\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=6914\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:84:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/tips/speeding-wordpress-site/\";}i:2;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:15927;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"4\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-11-16 15:57:06\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-11-16 13:57:06\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:4416:\"<p>It&#8217;s good to know that having a multi-language website involves a bit of effort, but there are also great perks that pay off. For example, you can <a href=\"https://www.quicksprout.com/2015/02/23/how-i-increased-my-search-traffic-by-47-from-translating-my-blog-into-82-languages/\">increase your search traffic up to 47%</a> by making your website available in more than one language. Not bad, right?</p>\n<p>If your website can be a good source of information for users that don&#8217;t know the main language, it&#8217;s a loss not to make it accessible for them too.Â If you invest a lot of time and energy to write valuable content, then you should also try to make it available as it can be. In the end, you want to share.</p>\n<p>You should know that changing the website language from the dashboard area is not enough. Your website&#8217;s structure is formed of different parts of posts, pages, menus or widgets. The content of those sections can be added directly to your language. However, there are strings attached, both from the theme and plugins, that you need to translate. Let&#8217;s take the following scenario: you have a blog website, and at the end of each article you can have a Read more part. Those specific words should be translated into your native language in order to facilitate access.</p>\n<div>\n<p>The .PO file includes the original texts and the translations in two columns. The .MO file incorporates the exact same contents as PO file. Keep in mind that the two files differ in their format. While a PO file is easy for humans to read, MO files are compiled and very easy for computers to read. Nonetheless, WordPress gets translations from the .MO files.</p>\n<p>Here are the steps you have to take in order to translate your website:</p>\n</div>\n<ol>\n<li>Install and activate the core <a href=\"https://wpml.org/\">WPML</a> plugins;</li>\n<li>Configure WPML (see theÂ <a href=\"http://wpml.org/documentation/getting-started-guide/\">Getting Started Guide</a>) by selectingÂ your default language, a set of active languages, and a language selector.</li>\n<li>Translate allÂ the elements of your website:\n<ol>\n<li>Content of your pages, posts and other custom elements (eg. projects);</li>\n<li>Menus;</li>\n<li>Widgets;</li>\n<li>Each language needs its own pair of files. In order to do this, please follow these steps for each language you want to have your website translated to:\n<ol>\n<li>Go toÂ <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/translate/projects/\">this link</a>;</li>\n<li>Select the theme that youÂ are using;</li>\n<li>Click on the language you would like to translate your website;</li>\n<li>You can suggest a new translation for any of the English original strings, seen on the left. Just click on Details button from the end of the line and add your suggestion;</li>\n<li>Once you finished your translation, go to the bottom of the page and select to Export all current as Portable Object Message Catalog (.po);</li>\n<li>You need to export one more file, the Machine Object Message (.mo),Â the same way you did on step 6;</li>\n<li>Go to <a href=\"https://make.wordpress.org/polyglots/teams/\">this link</a>;</li>\n<li>Find the WP Locale for the language you want to translate your website into.</li>\n<li>Rename both PO and MO files this way: themename-locale.po and themename-locale.mo. For example, if the theme is called Julia and you want to translate it in French, your files will be called julia-fr_FR.po and julia-fr_FR.mo;</li>\n<li>Upload the translation files, through FTP:\n<ol>\n<li>The theme translation files need to be added to wp-content/languages/themes folder;</li>\n<li>The plugins translation files need be added to wp-content/languages/plugins folder.</li>\n<li>The plugins for creating the PO/MO files. You can find some more details <a href=\"http://wplang.org/translate-theme-plugin/#2.1\">here</a>.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Anything that doesnât fall inside posts, pages or taxonomy goes into String Translation. This includes the siteâs tagline, general texts in Admin screens, widget titles and many other texts.Â You can find some further info about this right <a href=\"https://wpml.org/documentation/getting-started-guide/string-translation/\">here</a>.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>FAQs</h2>\n<h3>Are your themes compatible with WPML?</h3>\n<p>Yes â here is the official list of <a href=\"https://wpml.org/developer/pixelgrade/\">WPML certified themes</a>.</li>\n</ol>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:33:\"Creating a multi-language website\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:31:\"creating-multi-language-website\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-11-16 16:05:02\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-11-16 14:05:02\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:52:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=15927\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:92:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/tips/creating-multi-language-website/\";}i:3;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:19242;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"4\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2018-01-29 09:34:59\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2018-01-29 07:34:59\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:662:\"<p>Google Maps API requires a key in order to have access to its service. There are different places where this key is needed and the most important part is to generate it the right way. There&#8217;s a simple way to do that. Just goÂ  to <a href=\"https://console.developers.google.com/flows/enableapi?apiid=maps_backend&amp;keyType=CLIENT_SIDE&amp;reusekey=true\">Google Developer</a> console and follow the steps presented in the video below:</p>\n<p><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/253203883\" width=\"500\" height=\"281\" frameborder=\"0\" title=\"How to create a Google Maps API key\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe></p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:36:\"How to create a Google Maps API key?\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:26:\"create-google-maps-api-key\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2018-01-29 09:34:59\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2018-01-29 07:34:59\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:52:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=19242\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:87:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/tips/create-google-maps-api-key/\";}}}}}i:29;a:13:{s:7:\"term_id\";i:29;s:4:\"name\";s:16:\"Design and Style\";s:4:\"slug\";s:16:\"design-and-style\";s:10:\"term_group\";i:0;s:16:\"term_taxonomy_id\";i:29;s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:14:\"ht_kb_category\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"parent\";i:0;s:5:\"count\";i:5;s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:10:\"term_order\";s:1:\"2\";s:8:\"articles\";a:1:{i:0;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:145;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"5\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 13:13:15\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 10:13:15\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:2762:\"<p>We know that everyone is eager to shape their site according to their personality, values, and lifestyle. We&#8217;re happy to support this path not only by saying it, but also by providing real help. The whole options of our themes were designed to assist you in this customization process. We highly believe that offering a lot freedom can&#8217;t harm your final results, and that&#8217;s why we encourage you to use a theme for its specific goals, and make it yours at the same time.</p>\n<h2>Basic rules for an eye-candy look and feel</h2>\n<p>Each and every theme from our portfolio has <strong>a set of particular style rules</strong> that gives direction in order to help you build up a beautiful website. Yes, this is possible without having a solid knowledge of what a great design even means. These rules frame the core structure of the website and work as a strong infrastructure for the content and style layers that you&#8217;ll fill over time.</p>\n<p>We know for a fact that each website needs to have an unique voice which defines your charisma. That&#8217;s why we created a smart option systems to guide you through this process. From making handy changes of <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/design-and-style/style-changes/changing-colors/\">colors</a> till spacing adjustements and balacing <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/design-and-style/style-changes/changing-fonts/\" target=\"_blank\">fonts</a>, each step brings you closer to a striking result. On top of that, this flow will create a strong liaison with your personal branding.</p>\n<p>Also, you can challenge everything by smartly using the Custom CSS Editor field. Moreover, for any advanced customizations we highly suggest you to use a <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/getting-started/using-child-theme/\" target=\"_blank\">Child Theme</a>.</p>\n<p>Furthermore, learn how to change colors and adjust <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/design-and-style/style-changes/changing-fonts/\" target=\"_blank\">fonts</a> in a consistent way.</p>\n<h2>Why can&#8217;t I change everything in terms of style?</h2>\n<p>We&#8217;re a design studio with a relevant background in building WordPress themes. In fact, design is at the core at everything we do: from producing striking products to writing clean and witty code until crafting experience that counts. This being said, we take well-informed decisions in order to help you and give you the solutions you need in order to stand out from the digital crowd.</p>\n<p>Therefore, the simple, yet bold idea, to have a consistent website is something we deeply care about. With all these boundaries, even though we think they&#8217;re not real struggles, you know for a fact that you have a safety net, and your website is in the spotlight.</p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:23:\"Design & Style Overview\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:8:\"overview\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-04-20 10:52:56\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-20 07:52:56\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=145\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:63:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/design-and-style/overview/\";}}s:8:\"children\";a:2:{i:0;a:12:{s:7:\"term_id\";i:35;s:4:\"name\";s:13:\"Style Changes\";s:4:\"slug\";s:13:\"style-changes\";s:10:\"term_group\";i:0;s:16:\"term_taxonomy_id\";i:35;s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:14:\"ht_kb_category\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"parent\";i:29;s:5:\"count\";i:3;s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:10:\"term_order\";s:1:\"0\";s:8:\"articles\";a:2:{i:0;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:152;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 13:15:55\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 10:15:55\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:2393:\"<p>Colors have a powerful meaning for the general experience youâre crafting for people who bump into your website. Theyâre not just eye-candy pixels that grab attention; theyâre an integrated part of your branding, and it can impact your way of expression and communication.</p>\n<p>All of our themes have specific color options aligned to each element and feature. Weâve developed them in a way that allows you to change the majority of the websiteâs items without any effort: headings, body text, link, menu items, buttons or backgrounds. You can fastly customize the palette of colors to perfectly align it with your exquisite brand. Just use the color pickers and the live preview from our friendly and easy-to-use interface.</p>\n<h3><strong>Change the Colors</strong></h3>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><p>You canÂ play around with colors by the blink of an eye. Just navigate toÂ <em>Appearance âÂ Customize</em>, and click on<em>Â ColorsÂ </em>tab<em>.</em>Â ThereÂ you can accessÂ all the color options relatedÂ to that particular area. This way you can change, for example the colors for different elements from theÂ <strong>Header</strong>Â (Site Title, Navigation), fromÂ <strong>Main ContentÂ </strong>(background, page title) and more others.<strong>Â </strong></p>\n </p>\n<h3><strong>Takeaways</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Color meanings:</strong>Â choose colors that resonate with the statement you want to draw. For example, blue inspires safety, integrity, and peace, while yellow is translated into energy and joyfulness.</li>\n<li><strong>Keep the color scheme simple:</strong>Â as a common sense rule, try to focus your attention on a primary color (known as the base color as well) and add to it neutral colors such as white, black or gray. On the contrary, you can easily confuse the users and deliver mixed-feelings.</li>\n<li><strong>Maintain the contrast:</strong>Â for a bunch of situations, the dark colors make a good deal with the light ones. Stay away from using a light one for the background and another one pretty similar for the body text. To be more specific: a yellow text on a white background would be hard to read for everyone.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Take into account that the colors selected in theÂ <em>Customizer</em>Â are being applied on a general level. This way you know for sure that youâre consistent through the entire digital journey.</p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:15:\"Changing Colors\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:15:\"changing-colors\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-10-16 18:48:19\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-10-16 15:48:19\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=152\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:84:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/design-and-style/style-changes/changing-colors/\";}i:1;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:154;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"5\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 13:16:20\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-09-19 10:16:20\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:1803:\"<p>Weâre aÂ design-centered studioÂ who shares aÂ real passion for typography and all its characteristics: from admeasurement to spacing until hierarchy. Thatâs why we have aÂ strong focus on offering you enough room in order to find the right match between the type layer and your unique brandingÂ approach.</p>\n<h4><strong>Changing the font style and characteristics</strong></h4>\n<p>Using Listable themeÂ you can make different fontÂ adjustmentsÂ â change <strong>font family, weight, </strong>and<strong>Â size</strong>, set a <strong>letter spacing</strong>Â and choose aÂ <strong>text decoration</strong>.Â Depending on what particular text you&#8217;re willing to adjust, thereâs a specific path for each one.</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<p><p>You can simply play with the theme&#8217;s fonts for <b>Site and Page Title, Navigation, Body, Card Fonts any many other,Â </b>by going to <em>Appearance â Customize â Fonts</em>.</p>\n</p>\n\n<h4><strong>Takeaways</strong></h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Limit yourself to only a<strong>Â few fonts</strong>: itâs best to stick with two fonts but if youâre feeling ambitious, three is the maximum.</li>\n<li>We recommend you toÂ <strong>always use headings</strong>Â in order to create hierarchy and coherence within the structure of one page or another.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4><strong>Use PremiumÂ Fonts</strong></h4>\n<p>If you want to go even further, you can always appeal to custom fonts. You can quickly make that happen through seamless integration with <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/fonto/\">Fonto</a>, our side-project. For further details, you can read <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/plugins-integrations/fonto-premium-fonts/\">this helpful article</a> about <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/plugins-integrations/fonto-premium-fonts/\">this</a>Â plugin.</p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:14:\"Changing Fonts\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:14:\"changing-fonts\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-10-27 15:06:32\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-10-27 12:06:32\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=154\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:83:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/design-and-style/style-changes/changing-fonts/\";}}}i:1;a:12:{s:7:\"term_id\";i:36;s:4:\"name\";s:11:\"Custom Code\";s:4:\"slug\";s:11:\"custom-code\";s:10:\"term_group\";i:0;s:16:\"term_taxonomy_id\";i:36;s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:14:\"ht_kb_category\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"parent\";i:29;s:5:\"count\";i:2;s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:10:\"term_order\";s:1:\"1\";s:8:\"articles\";a:2:{i:0;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:289;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"8\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-11-02 12:12:54\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-11-02 09:12:54\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:1821:\"<p>If you aim for achieving more regarding the look-and-feel of your website, then play around with the options fromÂ the <strong>Customizer</strong>. There are plenty of them. However, if you are looking to make some specific styling changes concerning the <i>colors, fonts, </i>or<i> spaces,</i> the best option would be to use the <b>Custom CSS Editor</b>.</p>\n<p>All you have to do is to jump into the <b>CSS Editor</b> under <i>Appearance â Customize</i> and start adding your CSS while you can see your changes previewed live.</p>\n<p>Since recently, using CSS to alter the site appearance has been mainly a web designerâs job. Now, you should know that you donât need advanced designing or coding skills to do this work by yourself. Weâre giving you a helping hand by referring to some trustworthy resources to assist you:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Check out the <a href=\"https://en.support.wordpress.com/custom-design/css-basics/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">CSS Basics</a> article from WordPress.com, and donât forget to check the useful links at the bottom of the article.</li>\n<li>Or read the <a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/CSS\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Intro to CSS</a> section from WordPress Training community.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Don&#8217;t want to learn CSS? Use a plugin!</h4>\n<p>If you want to customize your website even more but you don&#8217;t want to touch any CSS code, you can use <a href=\"https://www.csshero.org/?rid=18277\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">CSS Hero</a> plugin. It is the most powerful tool that helps you to make live customizations without writing a single line of code. We checked it with our theme and it works beautifully. Read more about it <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/design-and-style/custom-code/making-style-changes-using-visual-css-editor/\">here</a>.</p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:27:\"Using the Custom CSS Editor\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:23:\"using-custom-css-editor\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-12-07 10:05:54\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-12-07 08:05:54\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=289\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:90:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/design-and-style/custom-code/using-custom-css-editor/\";}i:1;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:10095;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"5\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-06-13 19:52:58\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-06-13 16:52:58\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:3278:\"<div>\n<p>Even though you use the same WordPress theme that already hosts aÂ bunch of other websites across the world, this doesnât mean you need to follow the same visual path. You can tune it on your personality and create aÂ website that grabs the right kind of attention.Â Â We suggest you play around with the themeâs option and start from there, but if you want more than that, you can start customizing every element from your website.</p>\n<p>In this article, we will show you the easiest way possible of making specific style changes â by using <a href=\"https://www.csshero.org/?rid=18277\" data-cke-saved-href=\"https://www.csshero.org/?rid=18277\">CSS Hero</a> plugin. The truth is that one of the challenges you could face while editing your siteâs design is simply knowing how to find the correct selector to use. Using this plugin, you donât need to know CSS and or write any line of code. Everything is made simple byÂ point and click.</p>\n<h2><strong>Step 1 âÂ Install CSS Hero plugin</strong></h2>\n<p>In just aÂ few words, <a href=\"https://www.csshero.org/?rid=18277\" data-cke-saved-href=\"https://www.csshero.org/?rid=18277\">CSS Hero</a> plugin is a powerful tool that allows you to make quick and visual changesÂ to your website in no time, even if you&#8217;re aÂ beginner,Â have zero knowledge about CSS or you are a Master in CSS.</p>\n<p>Hereâs what you need to do:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Go toÂ <a href=\"https://www.csshero.org/?rid=18277\" data-cke-saved-href=\"https://www.csshero.org/?rid=18277\">CSS Hero website</a>Â and choose the plan that suits your needs better.</li>\n<li>Download the plugin on your computer.</li>\n<li>Go to your WordPress Dashboard to <em>Plugins â Add New</em></li>\n<li>Upload CSS Hero plugin and activate it.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now, even if you are on the backend or the frontend of your website, just click on <strong>Edit with CSS Hero</strong> tab from the admin toolbar and youâll get the interface of the pluginâs live editor.</p>\n<h2><strong>Step 2 âÂ Make the Right Visual Tweaks</strong></h2>\n<p>First of all, please keep in mind that you can use this CSS Hero plugin to customize the appearance of any WordPress theme you have. It works by allowing you to quickly add your CSS styles, which, in turn, offers you the freedom to override the default styles of your theme. No worries about the code generated when you make these changes &#8211; a separate stylesheet is automatically created so you will not lose your work when updating the theme. Everything is made easy for you.</p>\n<p>By using simple control, you can manage in real-time the changes that youâre making. This way, you will skip unpleasant surprises by the end of the journey. Make sure that you have aÂ clear goal when you start working with this plugin, and you know where you are heading to your website.</p>\n<p>The only reason why we recommend CSS HeroÂ is that weÂ tested and it works beautifully. Weâve been thrilled by the easiest of using it when making styleÂ customizations. Moreover, weâre always interested in finding solutions that are easy to use and donât require massive coding knowledge. Learn more about this plugin on <a href=\"https://www.csshero.org/?rid=18277\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">CSS Hero website</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:53:\"Making Style Changes Easier Using a Visual CSS Editor\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:44:\"making-style-changes-using-visual-css-editor\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-12-07 00:21:35\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-12-06 22:21:35\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:52:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=10095\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:111:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/design-and-style/custom-code/making-style-changes-using-visual-css-editor/\";}}}}}i:30;a:12:{s:7:\"term_id\";i:30;s:4:\"name\";s:17:\"Header and Footer\";s:4:\"slug\";s:17:\"header-and-footer\";s:10:\"term_group\";i:0;s:16:\"term_taxonomy_id\";i:30;s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:14:\"ht_kb_category\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"parent\";i:0;s:5:\"count\";i:4;s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:10:\"term_order\";s:1:\"3\";s:8:\"articles\";a:3:{i:0;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:211;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"8\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-10-27 11:06:15\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-10-27 08:06:15\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:4002:\"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The <a href=\"https://www.designcontest.com/logo-design/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">logo</a> is a crucial part of the branding process. Is what makes you-</span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">you</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, and a significant element to be recognized for by the right people. Because of its huge relevance, we offer you two options to play with: you can add a graphic symbol (such as an image) or a text version (logotype). You choose a font, and we help you fine-tune the logo after its personality.</span></p>\n<h2>Before you start</h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In order to properly make things happen with the font, we highly suggest you take into consideration these factors:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><b>File Formats</b> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br />\n</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">You should be aware that a logo looks best in a </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.png</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> or </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.svg</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> format with a transparent background. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If your logo file doesnât have a transparent background, itâs likely that your logo will partly cover the background image.</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><b>Logo Size</b><b><br />\n</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We encourage you to have a larger image for your logo. Try to use a high dimension of the logo, and weâll do the rest by scaling it. This way the logo will adapt to any screen size (both desktop and mobile).</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Adding a Logo Image</h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now that you know whatâs better to do when setting up your logo, hereâs what you have to do in order to upload it on your WordPress site:</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Open the </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Customizer</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> under </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Appearance</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and click onÂ <i>SiteÂ Identity.</i></span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the new panel that opens out click the <strong>Select</strong></span><strong>Â Logo</strong><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> button to open the </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Media Manager.</span></i></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Select an image that&#8217;s already in your </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Media Library</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, or upload a new one.</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When you finish just click on </span><b>Set as Logo</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and you&#8217;ll see the logo in the preview window.</span></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">To activate the logo on your site, click </span><b>Save &amp; Publish</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> button.</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It couldnât be easier than that, and youâve already made an important step in order to personalize your upcoming website.</span></p>\n<h2>Using a Text Version</h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you donât have any graphic symbol that stands for your business, we recommend you to choose the text option instead. Itâs a good switch if youâre careful with details like the font and its size. In this case, simply use the </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Site Title</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> field under </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Site Title &amp; Logo</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and style its font using the options from </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Customizer<em>â</em>Â Header</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:16:\"Adding your Logo\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:16:\"adding-your-logo\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2018-04-24 16:04:02\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2018-04-24 13:04:02\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=211\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:72:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/header-and-footer/adding-your-logo/\";}i:1;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:286;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-11-07 00:32:20\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-11-06 21:32:20\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:6387:\"<p>We all need landmarks in the digital world, right? However, talking about the ecosystem of a website, you should refer to the navigation menu as a comrade. In the end, is just a map that guidesÂ you to dig deeper and fully enjoyÂ the site experience.</p>\n<p>It may sound naive, but it is what makes users leave a website without hesitations. A bad navigation comes along with frustrations and an illogical flow. The good news is that WordPress includes a solid menu manager tool to keep people on track and convince them to come back. Who doesn&#8217;t aim for such a behavior, right?</p>\n<h2 class=\"section-title\">Step 1 &#8211; Create a Custom Menu</h2>\n<p>You can easily create navigation menus in WordPress. Log into your <em>Dashboard</em>, go to <em>Appearance â Customize</em>Â <em>â</em>Â <em>Menus a</em>nd click <strong>Add aÂ menu</strong>Â button.<br />\nNow you&#8217;re able to set the location of your menu by checking the field you find it suitable:<em>Â Footer, Primary Header, Secondary Header and Social Menu</em>.Once you have a convenient name for it, justÂ press the<strong> <em>Create Menu</em></strong><em>.Â </em></p>\n<h2 class=\"section-title\">Step 2 &#8211; Add Items to your Menu</h2>\n<p class=\"section-title\">Now that you have a menu and a location for it, all you needÂ to do is toÂ <strong>add menu items</strong> by:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Clicking on the <strong>Add Items</strong> button and choosing the menu item type from the list that appears on the right.</li>\n<li>After selecting the desired item from the list, please click <strong>Add to MenuÂ </strong>button.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>You can add several types of menu items to your custom menu such as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Page</strong>: Adds a link to another page onÂ your site.</li>\n<li><strong>Link</strong>:Â  Adds a custom URL linking to another site.</li>\n<li><strong>Category</strong>: Shows a feed of blog posts from a given category.</li>\n<li><strong>Tag</strong>:Â  Shows a feed of blog posts from a given tag.</li>\n<li><strong>Post</strong>:Â Links directly to a blog post on your site.</li>\n</ul>\n<br />\n<strong>NOTE</strong>: If the elements that you&#8217;d like to add to your menu are not available on the left side of the page, just click the <a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/Administration_Screens#Screen_Options\">Screen Options</a> button at the top right side of the page. Once you did that, a list of different modules will be displayed. You can check now all the missing elements from the menu</p>\n<h2 class=\"section-title\">Step 3 &#8211; Organize your Menu</h2>\n<p>With all the menu items in place, you can change theÂ order and the placement of the menu items by simply using the<strong> drag-and-drop</strong>Â gesture. Using the same system you can even create sub-menus or drop-down style menus. Just drag the individual items to the right and setÂ them under a parent tab. In case you want to revert your changes please drag the menu items to the left to make them parent again. Feel free to play around, and find the right scheme for your particularÂ needs.</p>\n<h2>Step 4 &#8211; Assign it to a MenuÂ Location</h2>\n<p class=\"section-title\">Everything is pretty much set once you reached this step. The next phaseÂ is to let WordPress know where youÂ need the navigation menu to be showcased. To do that, browse to the<strong>Â <em>MenuÂ Locations</em></strong>Â area and depending on what theme you&#8217;re using, you&#8217;ll be able to choose from the available Menu Locations. Simply assign the previously created menu to the desired Location, and you are off to the races.</p>\n<h4>Quick Tips:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The Magical Number Seven (plus or minus two)</strong><br />\nThis is because <em>short-term memory holds only seven items</em>. It&#8217;s a fact, not a wishful thinking thing. With fewer menu items, your visitorsâ eyes are less likely toÂ scan past important items. Every time you remove a menu item, the remaining items become more prominent. Challenge yourself to <strong>limit your navigation to five items</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>AvoidÂ Drop-Down Menus<br />\n</strong>By not using drop-down style menus, we reduce the possibilities of the website visitors to miss the relevant content. Keep it simple.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"frequently-asked-questions\" class=\"section-title\">FAQs</h2>\n<h4>How do I create a un-clickable parent tab for my sub-menu?</h4>\n<p>To create a menu item that is not clickable but will still contain sub-menus items, just add a <em>Custom Links</em> menu item and add a # symbol in the âLink Address (URL)â field.<br />\n<h4>Showing Items Only to Logged In/Out Users</h4>\n<p>Some links only make sense if a user is logged in or not. For example, you definitely want to show the âLog Inâ button only if a user is not already logged in on your website. In order to do that we will use the flexible <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/nav-menu-roles/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Nav Menu Roles</a> plugin, which will add some controls for each menu item in <em>Appearance â Menus</em>.</p>\n<h4>Adding a Call to Action Button Style</h4>\n<p>An effective call-to-action will drive your users to take your desired action. If you want to transform one of your menu items into such a button (see the &#8220;Add Listing&#8221; from the demo), you just need to add the &#8220;cta&#8221; class to that item. To do that, navigate to Appearance â Menus, enable the CSS Classes section from the Screen Options tab, then go to your menu item and simply add the &#8220;cta&#8221; class (see the <a href=\"https://cl.ly/1G41233B370G\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">guided animation</a>).</p>\n<p><strong>Additional Resources:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/managing-secondary-menu/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Managing the Secondary Menu</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/managing-search-suggestions-list/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Managing the Search Suggestions Menu</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/add-current-username-navigation-menu/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">How to add the Current Username to the Navigation Menu?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/create-log-link-menu/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">How to Create a Log-Out Link in Your Menu</a></li>\n</ul>\n</p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:24:\"Managing your Navigation\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:24:\"managing-your-navigation\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-10-16 18:25:53\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-10-16 15:25:53\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=286\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:80:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/header-and-footer/managing-your-navigation/\";}i:2;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:6745;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"5\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 15:36:14\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-19 12:36:14\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:3279:\"<p>The secondary menu is placed below the header bar and can be used on specific pages where you need another level of organization for your content.Â Weâre using on the demo for organizing the User Account area:</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://cl.ly/2h1U24162z2Z/Image%202016-01-06%20at%207.24.19%20am.png\" alt=\"image202016-01-0620at207-24-1920am\" /></p>\n<h3>Step 1 â Create the âSecondaryâ Menu</h3>\n<p>First, you need toÂ <a href=\"http://easywpguide.com/wordpress-manual/appearance/updating-the-menu/adding-a-new-menu/\">Create a Menu</a>Â by going toÂ <em>Appearance â Menus</em>Â and follow the regular WordPress process (moreÂ <a href=\"http://easywpguide.com/wordpress-manual/appearance/updating-the-menu/adding-a-new-menu/\">here</a>). Letâs call it âSecondary Menuâ.</p>\n<p>Note that you donât need to assign it yet to any menu location, as we will do this on the next steps.</p>\n<h3>Step 2 â Add Items to the Menu</h3>\n<p>From the left section, you can add links to the desired pages: My Account, Listings Dashboard, Add Listing, Bookmarks or any other ones (seeÂ <a href=\"http://cl.ly/1b2R210Z110p\">screenshot</a>)</p>\n<h3>Step 3 â Show the Menu only on Specific Pages</h3>\n<p>The last step is to<strong>Â </strong>show the menu only on relevant pages, as it doesnât make sense to have it for example on the âHomeâ page.</p>\n<p>In addition to theÂ <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/nav-menu-roles/\">Nav Menu Roles</a>Â plugin that you can use to display specific menu items depending on whether a user is logged in or not, we will use theÂ <strong>Conditional Menus</strong>Â (free).</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://themify.me/conditional-menus\">Conditional Menus</a>Â is a simple yet useful WordPress plugin which allows you to swap the menus as per specific conditions. In short, you can have different menus in different posts, pages, categories, archive pages, etc.</p>\n<p>AfterÂ <a href=\"http://easywpguide.com/wordpress-manual/plugins/adding-new-plugin/\">installing</a>Â and activatingÂ <a href=\"https://themify.me/download/6/\">the plugin</a>, go to Â <em>Appearance â MenusÂ <em>â Manage LocationsÂ </em></em>and add a newÂ <em>Conditional Menu</em>Â for theÂ <em>Secondary Menu area,</em>Â that will be shown only on the pages mentioned above:</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://cl.ly/2m0Q351b1B1h/Screen%20Recording%202016-01-06%20at%2007.43%20am.gif\" alt=\"\" /></p>\n<p><strong>Additional Readings:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Get theÂ <a href=\"http://themify.me/conditional-menus\">Conditional Menus</a>Â plugin (<a href=\"https://themify.me/\">Themify</a>)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://easywpguide.com/wordpress-manual/appearance/updating-the-menu/adding-a-new-menu/\">Adding a New Menu</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/header-and-footer/managing-your-navigation/\">Managing your Navigation</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/pages-and-content/managing-search-suggestions-list/\">Managing the Search Suggestions Menu</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/add-current-username-navigation-menu/\">How to add the Current Username to the Navigation Menu?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/create-log-link-menu/\">How to Create a Log Out Link in Your Menu</a></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:27:\"Managing the Secondary Menu\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:23:\"managing-secondary-menu\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-06-07 23:13:36\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-06-07 20:13:36\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=6745\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:79:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/header-and-footer/managing-secondary-menu/\";}}}i:33;a:12:{s:7:\"term_id\";i:33;s:4:\"name\";s:17:\"SEO and Analytics\";s:4:\"slug\";s:17:\"seo-and-analytics\";s:10:\"term_group\";i:0;s:16:\"term_taxonomy_id\";i:33;s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:14:\"ht_kb_category\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"parent\";i:0;s:5:\"count\";i:2;s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:10:\"term_order\";s:1:\"4\";s:8:\"articles\";a:1:{i:0;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:6304;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"5\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-03-21 17:17:27\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-03-21 15:17:27\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:2804:\"<p>Having a website without Google Analytics on it is like having a laptop without connection to Internet. If you want to go far, you need to gather relevant insights about your visitors. This way you&#8217;re taking well-informed decisions that will bring you concrete results.</p>\n<p>From specific facts (such as demographics) until in-depth data regarding time spent on a particular page or the flow of conversions, Google Analytics can provide you all this information.</p>\n<h2>Step 1 â How to start?</h2>\n<p>There are several plugins which can help you link this tool to your website, but our recommendation is the free version of theÂ <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">MonsterInsights</a>Â plugin. This suggestionÂ comes on an unbiased foundation, and it is based only on the fact that we tested and we&#8217;re happy with how thing worked out.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Log in into your <em>Dashboard</em>, go to <em>Plugins</em> and click on <strong>Add new</strong></li>\n<li>Type the name of the plugin (<strong>Monster Insights</strong>) directly in the search box from the top right corner</li>\n<li>Once you found it click on <strong>Install Now</strong>, and then on <strong>Activate</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>On the side menu of your <em>Dashboard</em> (under <em>Settings</em>) you now have a button named <em>Insights</em>.Â To properly set up the plugin you need toÂ authenticate with Google Analytics.</p>\n<h2>Step 2 â How to connect to Google Analytics?</h2>\n<p>This <a href=\"https://www.monsterinsights.com/docs/connect-google-analytics/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">article</a> explains the step-by-step process of installing and activating MonsterInsights on your WordPress website. It comes with a dedicated video and a bunch of screenshots to make sure you make a consistent setup and start with the right foot.</p>\n<h4>Tips</h4>\n<p>Other resources you shouldÂ consider in order to make the most out of Google Analytics:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>WPBeginnerâ<a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/how-to-install-google-analytics-in-wordpress/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">How to install Google Analytics in WordPress</a></li>\n<li>WPBeginnerâ<a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/beginners-guide-how-to-use-google-analytics-for-your-wordpress-site/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">How to use Google Analytics for your WordPress site</a></li>\n<li>WPMuDevâ<a href=\"https://premium.wpmudev.org/blog/google-analytics-guide/?omtr=b&amp;utm_expid=3606929-101.yRvM9BqCTnWwtfcczEfOmg.1&amp;utm_referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.ro%2F\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">A Comprehensive Guide to Google Analytics and Understanding Your WordPress Site Traffic</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:52:\"How to add Google Analytics to my WordPress website?\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:34:\"google-analytics-wordpress-website\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2018-05-29 22:37:19\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2018-05-29 19:37:19\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=6304\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:90:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/seo-and-analytics/google-analytics-wordpress-website/\";}}}i:31;a:12:{s:7:\"term_id\";i:31;s:4:\"name\";s:15:\"Social Networks\";s:4:\"slug\";s:15:\"social-networks\";s:10:\"term_group\";i:0;s:16:\"term_taxonomy_id\";i:31;s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:14:\"ht_kb_category\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"parent\";i:0;s:5:\"count\";i:8;s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:10:\"term_order\";s:1:\"5\";s:8:\"articles\";a:1:{i:0;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:276;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-11-01 22:55:32\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-11-01 19:55:32\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:3290:\"<p>We live in a world where sharing has become a natural way of acting and reacting. Weâre eager to let people know about amazing places, tasty food, or bold experiences. Thatâs why social icons are much more than a witty approach to spreading messages. In fact, they are a solidÂ gateway to encourage your audience to follow and connect with you by having a cordial and welcoming attitude. Moreover, it is a powerful strategy to <strong>create and consolidate a community</strong> which is relevant to your website.</p>\n<p>The following steps give you a helping hand to get theÂ social media icons. Just stick to the plan and you are going to succeed. Before starting, please make sure that you installed,Â  activated and connected JetPack plugin to yourÂ WordPress.com account.Â You can read more about thisÂ <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/getting-started/installing-the-theme/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">here</a>.</p>\n<h2>Step 1 &#8211; Create the Menu</h2>\n<p>The very first move is to go to <i>Appearance â Customize â Menus </i>and click on <strong>Add Menu</strong> button to <a href=\"http://easywpguide.com/wordpress-manual/appearance/updating-the-menu/adding-a-new-menu/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">create a new menu</a>, then give it a name like âSocial Menuâ, for instance.</p>\n<h2>Step 2 &#8211; Add Custom Links to your Social Profiles</h2>\n<p>All you have to do now is to add menu items that link to your social profiles by using the <a href=\"http://easywpguide.com/wordpress-manual/appearance/updating-the-menu/adding-a-custom-link-menu-item/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Custom Links</a> option. You find it on the left side of the panel. If it is easier, just check<a href=\"https://cl.ly/2b3I0r133r0x\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> this screenshot</a>.</p>\n<h2>Step 3 &#8211; Place the Menu</h2>\n<p>You are almost there! Now go to<i> Appearance â Customize â Menus â Manage Locations â <strong>&#8220;Social Menu&#8221;</strong></i>Â and set the menu that you just created.</p>\n<p>IfÂ there is no <em>&#8220;Social Menu&#8221;</em> location then you can add the social icons in the footer area, by going toÂ <em>AppearanceÂ âÂ CustomizeÂ âÂ WidgetsÂ â</em><em>Â Footer Area</em> and add a new <a href=\"https://en.support.wordpress.com/widgets/custom-menu-widget/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">&#8220;Custom Menu&#8221; Widget</a> with the above-created menu selected.</p>\n<h4>Which social icons are supported?</h4>\n<p>We support a bunch of social services, but we encourage you to be aware that not all of them brings real value. Also, donât abuse of these channels because nothing good will happen. Depending on your website and your goals search for the right social services. Start by finding out where your audience likes to spend time and try to create witty liaisons.</p>\n<p>However, hereâs the complete list: Email, RSS Feeds (links with âfeedâ or âRSSâ), Behance, Delicious, DeviantArt, Digg, Dribbble, Facebook, Flickr, FourSquare, GitHub, Google+, Instagram, LinkedIn, Pinterest, Reddit, Skype, SoundCloud, Spotify, StumbleUpon, Tumblr, Twitter, Vimeo, Vine, Vkontakte, Sina Weibo, Xing, Yahoo, AngelList, Yelp, LastFM, SlideShare, and Twitch.</p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:23:\"Displaying Social Icons\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:23:\"displaying-social-icons\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2018-05-28 10:33:24\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2018-05-28 07:33:24\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=276\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:77:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/social-networks/displaying-social-icons/\";}}}i:32;a:12:{s:7:\"term_id\";i:32;s:4:\"name\";s:20:\"Plugins Integrations\";s:4:\"slug\";s:20:\"plugins-integrations\";s:10:\"term_group\";i:0;s:16:\"term_taxonomy_id\";i:32;s:8:\"taxonomy\";s:14:\"ht_kb_category\";s:11:\"description\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"parent\";i:0;s:5:\"count\";i:11;s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:10:\"term_order\";s:1:\"6\";s:8:\"articles\";a:4:{i:0;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:377;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2016-11-16 15:06:49\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2016-11-16 13:06:49\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:2183:\"<p>We know how handy can be to use a page builder on your website. That&#8217;s why we tested the most common and trustworthy tools to make sure that everything works great with our themes. Use their drag-and-drop features to create complex layouts and fill them with buttons, charts, icons or many others content blocks.</p>\n<h3>What plugins have you tested?</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"https://elementor.com/\">Elementor</a>Â (free)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://codecanyon.net/item/visual-composer-page-builder-for-wordpress/242431?ref=pixelgrade\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Visual ComposerÂ </a>($34)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/siteorigin-panels/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">SiteOrigin Page Builder</a>Â (Free)</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.getmotopress.com/plugins/content-editor/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">MotoPress Content Editor</a>Â ($29)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.wpbeaverbuilder.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Beaver Builder</a>Â ($99)</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Where should I use them?</h3>\n<p>We recommend to make the most out of themÂ only for <b>presentation pages </b>and not for theÂ dynamicallyÂ related ones (eg. Blog Archive).</p>\n<h3>Do you offer customer support for those plugins?</h3>\n<div>No. Let us tell you why: we heavily tested them to make sure everything runs smoothlyÂ â none of their elements or styles weren&#8217;t specifically changed. For any questions regarding potential problems or any other concerns, please refer to their authors. They are the ones who can easily lend you a helping hand in order toÂ get things done.</div>\n<h3>Which one fits best my needs?</h3>\n<p>Each of the plugins mentioned above has their pros and cons. WeÂ recommendÂ <em>Elementor</em> but we encourage you to take over the<a href=\"http://www.codeinwp.com/blog/motopress-content-editor-vs-visual-composer-vs-siteorigin-page-builder-vs-beaver-builder/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Â MotoPress Content Editor vs Visual Composer vs SiteOrigin Page Builder vs Beaver BuilderÂ </a>comparison table and decide on your own, taking into consideration your specific needs and preferences.</p>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:25:\"Drag & Drop Page Builders\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:23:\"drag-drop-page-builders\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-06-09 00:00:33\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-06-08 21:00:33\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:50:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=377\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:82:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/plugins-integrations/drag-drop-page-builders/\";}i:1;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:7498;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-18 22:42:18\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-18 19:42:18\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:5448:\"<p>ListableÂ is offering seamless integration with many 3rd party plugins, rather than to strictly impose and limit the functionality of the theme.Â This flexibility allows you to juggle with a great variety ofÂ new ideas for your project, easily mixing various plugins to achieve your specific goals.</p>\n<p>Besides this, if you don&#8217;t need some functionality you simply don&#8217;t install that specific plugin â this way you will keep your site cleaner, far from the likely bloat that comes pre-packaged with similar products.</p>\n<p>All theÂ <strong>core functionality</strong>Â ofÂ ListableÂ is available throughÂ <strong>free</strong>Â plugins, but if you need to go even further, we&#8217;ve come along with aÂ <strong>curated list of pluginsÂ </strong>from well-known and respected authors.</p>\n<p>These are all theÂ <strong>Premium PluginsÂ (paid)</strong>Â used throughout our demo:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>WP Job Manager âÂ <a href=\"https://wpjobmanager.com/add-ons/bookmarks/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Bookmarks</a>Â (<strong>optional</strong>): Add the option to bookmark listings.</li>\n<li>WP Job Manager âÂ <a href=\"https://wpjobmanager.com/add-ons/job-tags/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Tags</a>Â (<strong>optional</strong>):Â Used to fine-grain your listings filtering.</li>\n<li>WP Job Manager âÂ <a href=\"https://wpjobmanager.com/add-ons/wc-paid-listings/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WooCommerce Paid Listings</a>Â (<strong>optional</strong>): Sell quantity based listing packages.</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.woothemes.com/products/woocommerce-subscriptions/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WooCommerce Subscriptions</a>Â (<strong>optional</strong>): Sell subscription-based listing packages.</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.woothemes.com/products/woocommerce-bookings/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WooCommerce Bookings</a>Â (<strong>optional</strong>): Offer reservations for certain listings.</li>\n<li>WP Job Manager âÂ <a href=\"https://astoundify.com/downloads/wp-job-manager-products/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Products</a>Â (<strong>optional</strong>): Display reservations right on the listing page.</li>\n<li>WP Job Manager âÂ <a href=\"https://astoundify.com/downloads/wp-job-manager-claim-listing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Claim Listing</a>Â (<strong>optional</strong>): Allow business owners to claim their listings.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://searchwp.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Search WP</a>Â (<strong>optional</strong>): Improve default WordPress search system.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://tinygiantstudios.co.uk/store/brands/brands-mike-jolley/auto-location/\">Auto Location</a> (optional):Â Improve the location field by adding an auto-suggests option.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://astoundify.com/products/wp-job-manager-extended-location/\">Extended Location</a> (<strong>optional</strong>):Â Allow the users choose where the business is located on the map.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.csshero.org/?rid=18277\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">CSS Hero</a> (<strong>optional</strong>): Beautifully customize your website without writing any line of code.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>*Note that the theme doesnât comeÂ bundledÂ with any of these plugins.</strong>Â They are paid add-ons (optional) that extend the site functionality â we&#8217;re only offering a seamless visual interface integration, while support for each plugin is offered by their authors.</p>\n<h3>Do I need those premium plugins?</h3>\n<p>They areÂ <strong>not mandatory</strong>Â for the theme â read their description first and install only if you need that extra functionality.</p>\n<h3>Why are the plugins not bundled within the theme?</h3>\n<p>Besides their licenses, there were numerous cases where bundling a plugin was a very bad practice â both in terms of security and portability. You can read more about this subject onÂ <a href=\"http://wptavern.com/1000-wordpress-themes-on-envato-market-potentially-affected-by-revolution-slider-security-vulnerability\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WP Tavern</a>Â orÂ <a href=\"http://marketblog.envato.com/news/plugin-vulnerability/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Envato Blog</a>.</p>\n<h2>FAQ</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-charge-money-listings-publishing/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Can I charge Money for Listings Publishing?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-restrict-fields-specific-package/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Can I restrict some fields for a specific package?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-edit-add-new-listing-fields/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Can I edit or add new listing fields?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/how-do-i-add-extra-social-media-profiles/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">How do I add Extra Social Media Profiles?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/plugins-integrations/drag-drop-page-builders/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Can I use Drag &amp; Drop Page Builder plugins?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-use-facetwp-wpml-plugins-listable-theme/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">FacetWP and WPML plugins with Listable theme</a></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:48:\"Premium Plugins To Extend Listable Functionality\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:45:\"premium-plugins-extend-listable-functionality\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-12-06 12:34:16\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-12-06 10:34:16\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=7498\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:104:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/plugins-integrations/premium-plugins-extend-listable-functionality/\";}i:2;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:7502;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-18 22:46:04\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-18 19:46:04\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:5003:\"<p>As a follow-up for ourÂ <a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/plugins-integrations/premium-plugins-extend-listable-functionality/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Premium Plugins To Extend the Theme Functionality</a>Â article, we thought it useful to compile a list of popular plugins we&#8217;ve found to be working fine with Listable, despite the fact that we haven&#8217;t set out to integrate with them. So please bear in mind that we haven&#8217;t committed ourselves to maintain a smooth integration with them. They just follow the standards (as do we) and nice things happen as a consequence.</p>\n<p>Some of these plugins are in active use on our demo, while some were just tested due to their notoriety or interesting functionality.</p>\n<h2>Search Engine Optimization</h2>\n<p>SEO may not be what it used to be (we believe this to be a good thing) but it doesn&#8217;t hurt to keep your site in top condition.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wordpress-seo/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">YOAST SEO</a>Â (we use this highly popular, free plugin on theÂ <em>demo</em>)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Performance</h2>\n<p>Continuing with the SEO optimization, there is no better way to boost up your site then by keeping it running fast. One useful tool (but not a fix-all solution) is the caching plugin:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://wp-rocket.me/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WP Rocket</a>Â (used on theÂ <em>demo</em>) &#8211; Â While a paid option, this will surely make up for it through sheer simplicity and ease of mind. It&#8217;s probably the best caching plugin around for the most of us (<a href=\"http://wp-rocket.me/features/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">some hints</a>Â supporting this claim).</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/w3-total-cache/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">W3 Total Cache</a>Â &#8211; A classic caching plugin, with a truckload of options. So we would recommend it only to those that are more technically inclined.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/wp-super-cache/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WP Super Cache</a>Â &#8211; The other highly popular plugin (from Automattic, the makers of WordPress), with more simplicity.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Design &amp; Editing</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://codecanyon.net/item/visual-composer-page-builder-for-wordpress/242431\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Visual Composer</a>Â &#8211; A highly popular, premium page builder plugin that aims to allow you to easily create presentation pages.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/siteorigin-panels/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">SiteOrigin Page Builder</a>Â &#8211; AÂ <em>free</em>Â alternative page builder, powerful and quite easy to use.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/say-what/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Say What?</a>Â &#8211; Easily change any string on your website without editing code &#8211; Nice!</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/nav-menu-roles/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Nav Menu Roles</a>Â &#8211; used on our demo. Using this free plugin you can display/hide menu items depending on whether a user is logged in or nor, or if it has certain credentials or not.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/menu-icons/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Menu Icons</a>Â &#8211; Add icons to your menu items (we&#8217;re using it on the demo, under theÂ <a href=\"http://listable-help.pixelgrade.com/support/solutions/articles/4000067729-managing-the-search-suggestions-menu\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Search menu</a>).</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://plugins.smyl.es/wp-job-manager-emails/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WP Job Manager Emails</a> (optional): Allows various email notifications. (eg. expired listings, new listing submission &amp; more)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Selling Stuff</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/woocommerce/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WooCommerce</a>Â (used on theÂ <em>demo</em>)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Others</h2>\n<p>There remains onlyÂ <strong>one plugin</strong>Â that doesn&#8217;t fit any category (and all at the same time).Â <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/jetpack/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Jetpack</a>Â from Automattic. We wouldÂ <strong>highly recommend</strong>Â you make this plugin your best friend and use it on all your WordPress installations as it will empower you with simple but powerful tools, starting from visual ones (tiled galleries, sliders, and so on), forms, comments, social sharing, and going to performance optimizations like Photon (effectively a free CDN) and security/monitoring. You will thank us later.</p>\n<h2>FAQ</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/faq/can-use-wp-job-manager-stats-listable/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Can I use WP Job Manager â Stats with Listable?</a></li>\n</ul>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:38:\"Other Plugins Compatible With Listable\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:27:\"plugins-compatible-listable\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 18:05:36\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-05-31 15:05:36\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=7502\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:86:\"https://pixelgrade.com/docs/listable/plugins-integrations/plugins-compatible-listable/\";}i:3;a:25:{s:2:\"ID\";i:6510;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"6\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2017-04-25 16:37:51\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-25 13:37:51\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:14743:\"<p class=\"intro\"><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/fonto/\">Fonto</a> is an in-house WordPress pluginÂ that gives you a helping hand when it comes to adding a new font to your website. Since there are plenty of possibilities to mix and match, we think that having such a reliable tool next to you will highly facilitate the process of decision-making. With Fonto you know for sure that you use your favorite fonts in the right way on your website.</p>\n<p>In this article, we will lead you through the journey of how to easily use your <strong>premium fonts</strong> into any WordPress site.</p>\n<p>For starting adding a new font just go to your WordPress <em>DashboardÂ â Fonts â</em><strong> Add New</strong><em>.Â </em>Then follow the two steps below regarding <strong>Font Source</strong> and <strong>Weights &amp; Styles Matching</strong>.</p>\n<h3>1. Font Source</h3>\n<p>There are twoÂ different ways to embed a font to your website. You can publish your fonts by using either an embed code through a Web Font Service or by downloading a self-hosting kit and hosting the fonts on your own server.</p>\n<h4>Web Font Service</h4>\n<p>Most of the premium type foundries are giving you a simple JavaScript or CSS code to insert in your website which automatically loads the fonts. Upon creating your project kit, you will be prompted to copy and paste an HTML code between the &lt;head&gt; and &lt;/head&gt; tags of your website.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-web-font-service-embed.png\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-6541 size-full\" src=\"https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-web-font-service-embed.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"761\" height=\"488\" srcset=\"https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-web-font-service-embed.png 761w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-web-font-service-embed-300x192.png 300w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-web-font-service-embed-50x32.png 50w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-web-font-service-embed-600x385.png 600w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-web-font-service-embed-330x212.png 330w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-web-font-service-embed-420x269.png 420w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-web-font-service-embed-115x74.png 115w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-web-font-service-embed-170x109.png 170w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 761px) 100vw, 761px\" /></a></p>\n<p>If you&#8217;re using services like <em>Fonts.com</em>, <em>Typekit</em> or <em>Typography.com</em>, you areÂ able to paste the provided code into <em>Fonts Loading / Embed Code</em> field as it is, and it will automatically be inserted in the &lt;head&gt; area of your website.</p>\n<h4>Self-Hosted</h4>\n<p>If you have a self-hosting kit containing your fonts in a Web font format, you can use this option to deploy your fonts directly from your server. Follow the video or the steps below to get the font loaded:</p>\n<p><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/210610256\" width=\"500\" height=\"281\" frameborder=\"0\" title=\"Fonto - Adding Self-Hosted Fonts\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Download the fonts files to your computer.</li>\n<li>Make sure that you have all the necessary font formats to display the Web fonts in all major browsers. There should be some Web Open Font Format (.woff or .woff2) files included. If you have onlyÂ the TrueType (.ttf) or OpenType (.otf) format, you can use the FontSquirrelÂ <a href=\"https://www.fontsquirrel.com/tools/webfont-generator\">Webfont Generator</a> to create the font formats you need to support all the major browsers.</li>\n<li>FromÂ <strong>Add New Font</strong> screen from <em>WordPress Dashboard</em>, afterÂ selecting the<strong> Self-Hosted option</strong>, click on the <strong>Add </strong>or<strong> Upload Files</strong> button and select to upload all the fonts files that you have.<strong>*Note</strong> that if you receive an error like <em>&#8220;Sorry, this file type is not permitted for security reasons.&#8221; </em>please follow <a href=\"http://freewptp.com/fix-wordpress-issue-sorry-this-file-type-is-not-permitted-for-security-reasons/\">this</a> article for more details.</li>\n<li>Insert in the &#8220;Embed Code&#8221; area the code received within the self-hosting kit. It should be a CSS code with some @font-face declarations:\n<pre>@font-face {\r\n   font-family: \'Font Name\';\r\n   src: url(\'font-name-file.woff2\') format(\'woff2\'),\r\n   url(\'font-name-file.woff\') format(\'woff\');\r\n}</pre>\n</li>\n<li>The last step is to copy theÂ <em>URL Path</em>Â field and paste it before each URL in the Embed Code field. The example code will look like this:\n<pre>@font-face {\r\n   font-family: \'Name of the font\';\r\n   src: url(\'<strong>http://yourwebsite.com/wp-content/uploads/fonts/11148/</strong>name-of-the-font-file.woff2\') format(\'woff2\'),\r\n   url(\'<strong>http://yourwebsite.com/wp-content/uploads/fonts/11148/</strong>name-of-the-font-file.woff\') format(\'woff\');\r\n}</pre>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Next, you have to match the fonts variations as explained at the second step.</p>\n<h3>2. Weights &amp; Styles Matching</h3>\n<p>Depending on the service you&#8217;re using, you should note how the fonts variations (weights and styles) are definedÂ within the <strong>font-family</strong> CSS rule.</p>\n<h4><strong>1. Fonts are grouped together in a single &#8220;Font Family&#8221; name</strong></h4>\n<p>When you have only one font name likeÂ <em>&#8220;Proxima Nova&#8221;,</em>Â you just need to enter the font name, and only check the available variations loaded through the font package:</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-6540 size-full\" src=\"https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1403\" height=\"725\" srcset=\"https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2.png 1403w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-300x155.png 300w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-768x397.png 768w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-1024x529.png 1024w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-50x26.png 50w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-600x310.png 600w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-330x171.png 330w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-420x217.png 420w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-115x59.png 115w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-170x88.png 170w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-1200x620.png 1200w, https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/fonto-fonts-referenced-same-name-2-900x465.png 900w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1403px) 100vw, 1403px\" /></p>\n<p>ServicesÂ that are offering this option:Â <em>Typekit.comÂ </em>orÂ <em>Fonts.com</em>Â through<em>Â </em><a href=\"https://www.fonts.com/support/faq/family-grouping\"><em>Family Grouping</em></a> option.</p>\n<h4><strong>2. Font Names are Referenced Individually</strong></h4>\n<p>When you have multiple font names likeÂ <em>&#8220;ProximaNW01-Regular&#8221;</em> and <em>&#8220;ProximaNW01-RegularItalic&#8221; </em>you need to pair the provided fonts names with their matching weights and styles. Note that there might be weights and styles that don&#8217;t have a font name available, which is totally fine as you don&#8217;t need to use all fonts variations.</p>\n<p><iframe src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/210618166\" width=\"500\" height=\"433\" frameborder=\"0\" title=\"Fonto - Font Names are Referenced Individually\" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe></p>\n<p>Services offering this option:<em> Fonts.com, Typography.com</em></p>\n<h3>3.Â Publish your Font</h3>\n<p>Once you finished the two steps above, hit the <strong>Publish</strong> button from the right sidebar to save the font.</p>\n<p>To apply your fonts to your site content, we will use the <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/customify/\">Customify</a> plugin which already has an integration with <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/plugins/fonto/\">Fonto</a>, to make it even easier to change the fonts. Note that if you use any of our themes, Customify should be already installed and activated.</p>\n<p>Go to <em>Appearance â Customize</em> and wherever you have a <em>Font Field</em> you will see your font at the top of the list:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/fonto-change-font.gif\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-8127\" src=\"https://pixelgrade.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/fonto-change-font.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"982\" height=\"424\" /></a></p>\n<p>And that&#8217;s it! Your favorite fonts, up and running in a matter of minutes &#x1f44f;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>FrequentlyÂ Used Web Fonts Services</h3>\n<p>Most of the type foundries offer their fonts directly from their servers. All you have to do is to copy the provided embed code and do the weights and styles matching.Â We made a few use-cases with most popular foundries:</p>\n<h4>1. Fonts.com</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Firstly, you need to create an accountÂ on <a href=\"http://Fonts.com\">Fonts.com</a>;</li>\n<li>Select the font you want to use for your website and assign it to a project. ForÂ some detailed instructions about how to do that you can check theÂ following article:Â <a href=\"https://www.fonts.com/web-fonts/instructions\">https://www.fonts.com/web-fonts/instructions</a></li>\n<li>Once everything is set up, all you have to do is to select your project, select the <em>Publish Options</em> option and copy all the JavaScript code from <em>Option 1: JavaScript</em> tab.</li>\n<li>In your website dashboard,Â go to <em>Fonts â </em><strong>Add New</strong> andÂ add a name for your new font.</li>\n<li>Select theÂ <em>Web Font Service</em> option and paste the code from point 3 inside theÂ <em>Fonts Loading / Embed Code</em> area.</li>\n<li>Now,Â you have to select the <em>Font Names are Referenced Individually</em> option from theÂ <em>Weights &amp; Styles Matching</em> section.</li>\n<li>For each variation of your font, you need to add the specific name.</li>\n<li>Let&#8217;s have the <a href=\"https://www.fonts.com/font/adobe/trajan\">Trajan</a> font, for example. As you can see, we only have the <em>Regular</em> and <em>Bold</em> options. In the <em>Publish Options</em> panel on Fonts.com (the same one from the point 3), you can see theÂ <em>Reference Your Web Fonts Directly</em> area. In this field, you have the name of the two variations of the font:<em><br />\n</em><em>&#8211; font-family:&#8217;Trajan W01 Regular&#8217;</em> for the <em>Regular</em> font<br />\n&#8211;Â <em>font-family:&#8217;Trajan W01 Bd&#8217;</em> for the <em>Bold</em> one.</li>\n<li>In the new fields available on Fonto, you need to add the name as it goes:<br />\n&#8211; for the <em>Regular</em> font you have to use theÂ <em>Regular 400</em> field and add the nameÂ <em>Trajan W01 Regular;<br />\n</em>&#8211; for the <em>Bold</em> font you have to use the <em>Bold 700</em> field and add the nameÂ <em>Trajan W01 Bold;</em></li>\n<li>Hit the <em>Publish</em> button and that&#8217;s all.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>2. Typekit.com</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Firstly, you need to create an accountÂ on <a href=\"http://typekit.com/\">TypeKit.com</a></li>\n<li>Select the font you want to use for your website and assign it to a project. ForÂ some detailed instructions about how to do that you can check theÂ following article: <a href=\"https://helpx.adobe.com/typekit/using/add-fonts-website.html\">https://helpx.adobe.com/typekit/using/add-fonts-website.html</a></li>\n<li>Go to <em>Kit Editor</em>.</li>\n<li>Click on<strong> Embed code</strong> button and copy all the embed code.</li>\n<li>In your website dashboard,Â go to <em>Fonts â </em><strong>Add New</strong> andÂ add a name for your new font.</li>\n<li>Select theÂ <em>Web Font Service</em> option and paste the code from point 4 inside theÂ <em>Fonts Loading / Embed Code</em> area.</li>\n<li>Make sure that you have checked theÂ <em>Fonts are grouped together in a single &#8220;Font Family&#8221; name</em> optionÂ in theÂ <em>Weights &amp; Styles Matching</em> area.</li>\n<li>Go back to the <em>Kit Editor</em> in Typekit and click onÂ <em>Using fonts in CSS</em>Â the <em>Selectors</em> area, on the left side of the page.</li>\n<li>Copy the text (without commas) in the first field of the modalÂ that appeared on the page.</li>\n<li>Go back to your dashboard and paste the text from point 9 in theÂ <em>Font Family Name</em> field.</li>\n<li>Back in the <em>Kit Editor</em>, have a look at the <em>Weights &amp; Styles</em> area, on the left side of the page.Â All the options available here need to be checked in the <em>Available Font Variations</em>Â areaÂ back in your dashboard.</li>\n<li>Once you checked all the variations, just hit <strong>Publish</strong> button.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>3 Typography.com</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Firstly, you need to create an accountÂ on <a href=\"https://www.typography.com/\">Typography.com</a></li>\n<li>Select the font you want to use for your website and assign it to a project. ForÂ some detailed instructions about how to do that you can check theÂ following article: <a href=\"https://dashboard.typography.com/user-guide/welcome\">https://dashboard.typography.com/user-guide/welcome</a></li>\n<li>Go to the top right button where it says &#8220;Welcome, X&#8221; and click on <em>Cloud Dashboard</em> area.</li>\n<li>Select the project that you just created.</li>\n<li>Click onÂ <em>Tools</em> button and copy all the code from the <em>CSS Key</em> field.</li>\n<li>In your website dashboard,Â go to <em>Fonts â </em><strong>Add New</strong> andÂ add a name for your new font.</li>\n<li>Select theÂ <em>Web Font Service</em> option and paste the code from theÂ point 5 inside theÂ <em>Fonts Loading / Embed Code</em> area.</li>\n<li>Click on the <em>Font Styles</em> tab of your project and look for the <em>font-family</em> used for the font.</li>\n<li>Copy the <em>font-family</em> and paste it in your dashboard, on theÂ <em>Font Family Name</em> field (without commas).</li>\n<li>Check all the variations available for the font, in <em>Typography.com</em> and make sure that all theÂ options inÂ theÂ <em>Available Font Variations</em> are checked.</li>\n<li>Hit the <strong>Publish</strong> button.</li>\n</ol>\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:58:\"Fonto â A Better Solution for Premium Fonts in WordPress\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:19:\"fonto-premium-fonts\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2017-04-26 09:10:47\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2017-04-26 06:10:47\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:51:\"https://pixelgrade.com/?post_type=ht_kb&#038;p=6510\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:5:\"ht_kb\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";s:12:\"external_url\";s:78:\"https://pix